 N. Dhebar|Uchharangrai Navalshankar Dhebar]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Indian National Congress]]|years=1959}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Neelam Sanjiva Reddy]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Devakanta Barua]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=President of the [[Indian National Congress]]|years=1978\u20131984}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rajiv Gandhi]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[B. V. Keskar]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Ministry of Information and Broadcasting (India)|Union Minister of Information and Broadcasting]]|years=9 June 1964 \u2013 11 January 1966}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Kodardas Kalidas Shah]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Gulzarilal Nanda]]<br />{{small|Acting}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of India]]|years=24 January 1966 \u2013 24 March 1977}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Morarji Desai]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Planning Commission (India)|Planning Commission]]|years=24 January 1966 \u2013 24 March 1977}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[M. C. Chagla|Mahommedali Currim Chagla]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Union Minister of External Affairs]]|years=6 September 1967 \u2013 13 February 1969}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Dinesh Singh (Uttar Pradesh politician)|Dinesh Singh]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Morarji Desai]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Finance (India)|Union Minister of Finance]]|years=16 January 1969 \u2013 15 March 1971}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Yashwantrao Chavan]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Home Affairs (India)|Union Minister of Home Affairs]]|years=27 June 1970 \u2013 4 February 1973}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Swaran Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (India)|Union Minister of Defence]]|years=1 December 1975 \u2013 25 December 1975}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Bansi Lal]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|rows=2|before=[[Charan Singh]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Prime Minister of India]]|years=14 January 1980 \u2013 31 October 1984}}\n{{s-aft|rows=2|after=[[Rajiv Gandhi]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Planning Commission (India)|Planning Commission]]|years=14 January 1980 \u2013 31 October 1984}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Chidambaram Subramaniam]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of Defence (India)|Union Minister of Defence]]|years=16 January 1980 \u2013 15 January 1982}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[R. Venkataraman|Ramaswamy Venkataraman]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[P. V. Narasimha Rao|Narasimha Rao]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Minister of External Affairs (India)|Union Minister of External Affairs]]|years=19 July 1984 \u2013 31 October 1984}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Rajiv Gandhi]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n}} \n{{Prime Ministers of India}}\n{{Bharat Ratna}}\n{{Indian National Congress Presidents}}\n{{Ministers of Information and Broadcasting}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gandhi, Indira}}\n[[Category:Indira Gandhi|*]]\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:4th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century women rulers]]\n[[Category:Assassinated heads of government]]\n[[Category:Assassinated Indian politicians]]\n[[Category:Bandung Conference attendees]]\n[[Category:Children of Prime Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:People from Raebareli]]\n[[Category:Deaths by firearm in India]]\n[[Category:Defence Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Female defence ministers]]\n[[Category:Female foreign ministers]]\n[[Category:Finance Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Indian Hindus]]\n[[Category:People associated with Santiniketan]]\n[[Category:Indian socialists]]\n[[Category:Kashmiri people]]\n[[Category:Lenin Peace Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Ministers for External Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Information and Broadcasting of India]]\n[[Category:Ministers of Internal Affairs of India]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Andhra Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Lok Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Nehru\u2013Gandhi family]]\n[[Category:People educated at Badminton School]]\n[[Category:People murdered in Delhi]]\n[[Category:People of the Emergency (India)]]\n[[Category:People who died in office]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Indian National Congress]]\n[[Category:Prime Ministers of India]]\n[[Category:Rajya Sabha members from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Bharat Ratna]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Cabinet of India]]\n[[Category:Women leaders of India]]\n[[Category:Women members of the Lok Sabha]]\n[[Category:Women prime ministers]]\n[[Category:Victims of Sikh terrorism]]\n[[Category:Assassination of Indira Gandhi]]\n[[Category:5th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:6th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:7th Lok Sabha members]]\n[[Category:State funerals in India]]\n[[Category:Heads of regimes who were later imprisoned]]\n", "name_user": "Twofingered Typist", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLegacy:rem dupl WP links; added WP links; wording; added citation, rem tag; edit for flow", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indira_Gandhi"}
{"title_page": "Non-Zionism", "text_new": "'''Non-Zionism''' is the political stance of [[Jews]] who \"were [or are] willing to help support Jewish settlement in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] (...) but will not come on [[aliyah]].\"<ref name = \"polish\">David Polish, ''Prospects for Post-Holocaust Zionism'', in Moshe David (editor), ''Zionism in Transition'', Institute of Contemporary Jewry, Hebrew University of Jerusalem, Arno Press, 1980, p.315.</ref>\n\nThe trend began in the [[United States]] in the first few decades of the 20th century when \"an increasingly large section of Americanized Jewish opinion began to shift away from [[anti-Zionism]] (...) either to pro-Zionism or non-Zionism. (...) The non-Zionists were willing to offer the diaspora Jews a Jewish homeland fiscal and diplomatic counsel, not for their own benefit or spiritual comfort but for those Jews who chose to reside there.\"<ref name = \"Feldman\">Egal Feldman, ''Catholics and Jews in Twentieth-Century America'', University of Illinois Press, 2001, p.40.</ref>\n\n==Difference from anti-Zionists==\n[[Yoram Dinstein]] gave this distinction: \"There is a marked difference between non-Zionism and [[anti-Zionism]]. A non-Zionist may challenge the theoretical underpinning of the concept of an 'ingathering of the exiles' in an independent [[Jewish State]]. If Jewish, he or she will not choose to live in [[Israel]], nor will he approve or reject the notion of other Jews living there in the Jewish State of Israel (...) but anti-Zionists do not find it sufficient to be dissatisfied with a decision made and implemented a long time ago. They are not content with a critical assessment of the situation confined to an historical (and, accordingly, a theoretical) framework. Not merely do they have an adverse opinion about the establishment of Israel in the past, but they contest the legitimacy of Israel as a State in the present time and the future.\"<ref>[[Yoram Dinstein]], ''Anti-Semitism, Anti-Zionism and the United Nations'' in ''Israel's Yearbook of Human Rights'', Faculty of Law, Tel-Aviv University, vol.17, Martinus Nijhoff Publishers, 1987, p.16.</ref>\n\n==Contemporary definitions==\n\n===Non-position===\nNon-Zionism has also been defined in terms of a non-position on Zionism. On online Jewish magazine ''Galus Australis'', Anthony Frosh has defined a non-Zionist Jews as a Jew \"who does not have any particular political relationship (positive or negative) with the State of Israel, or at least little more of a relationship than they would have with some other 3rd party state.\"<ref>Frosh, Anthony (30 August 2009). [http://galusaustralis.com/2009/08/non-zionism-an-under-recognised-non-position/ \"Non-Zionism: an Under-Recognised Non-Position\"]. ''Galus Australis''. {{webarchive|url=http://web.archive.org/web/20111008133204/http://galusaustralis.com/2009/08/1529/non-zionism-an-under-recognised-non-position/|date=8 October 2011}}. Retrieved 22 April 2020.</ref>\n\n=== Haredi non-Zionism===\nGenerally, those groups of [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi]] (Western) [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] Jews who participate in the Israeli government but do not believe in the religious ideology of Zionism are known as \"non-Zionists\".  The most prominent non-Zionist Haredi group is [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]]. This is in contrast to the [[Religious Zionism|religious Zionist]] [[Mizrachi (political party)|Mizrachi party]] (which believes the State of Israel to be the beginning of the redemption); and also in contrast to the anti-Zionist Haredi groups, such as [[Satmar (Hasidic dynasty)|Satmar]] and the [[Edah HaChareidis|Edah Charedis]], that openly oppose Zionism and have little to no interaction with the State of Israel and no representation in its government. Unlike the older definition, many live in the State of Israel. They tend to be extremely pro-Israel politically, as can be seen in such publications as [[Mishpacha]] and [[Hamodia]]. [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]] Haredi Jews may refer to themselves as Zionist.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Gideon Shimoni, ''From Anti-Zionism to Non-Zionism in Anglo Jewry, 1917-1937'', Jewish Journal of Sociology, 28 (1986), pp.19-48\n* Gideon Shimoni, ''The Non-Zionists in Anglo Jewry, 1937-1948''.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Bennett Muraskin, ''[http://www.vcn.bc.ca/outlook/current_issue/May-Jun%2007/Anti-Zionism.pdf Anti-Zionism and Non-Zionism in Jewish Life\u2014Past and Present]'',\n{{Zionism}}\n[[Category:Political theories]]\n[[Category:Types of Zionism]]\n", "text_old": "'''Non-Zionism''' is the political stance of [[Jews]] who \"were [or are] willing to help support Jewish settlement in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]] (...) but will not come on [[aliyah]].\"<ref name = \"polish\">David Polish, ''Prospects for Post-Holocaust Zionism'', in Moshe David (editor), ''Zionism in Transition'', Institute of Contemporary Jewry, Hebrew University of Jerusalem, Arno Press, 1980, p.315.</ref>\n\nThe trend began in the [[United States]] in the first few decades of the 20th century when \"an increasingly large section of Americanized Jewish opinion began to shift away from [[anti-Zionism]] (...) either to pro-Zionism or non-Zionism. (...) The non-Zionists were willing to offer the diaspora Jews a Jewish homeland fiscal and diplomatic counsel, not for their own benefit or spiritual comfort but for those Jews who chose to reside there.\"<ref name = \"Feldman\">Egal Feldman, ''Catholics and Jews in Twentieth-Century America'', University of Illinois Press, 2001, p.40.</ref>\n\n==Difference from anti-Zionists==\n[[Yoram Dinstein]] gave this distinction: \"There is a marked difference between non-Zionism and [[anti-Zionism]]. A non-Zionist may challenge the theoretical underpinning of the concept of an 'ingathering of the exiles' in an independent [[Jewish State]]. If Jewish, he or she will not choose to live in [[Israel]], nor will he approve or reject the notion of other Jews living there in the Jewish State of Israel (...) but anti-Zionists do not find it sufficient to be dissatisfied with a decision made and implemented a long time ago. They are not content with a critical assessment of the situation confined to an historical (and, accordingly, a theoretical) framework. Not merely do they have an adverse opinion about the establishment of Israel in the past, but they contest the legitimacy of Israel as a State in the present time and the future.\"<ref>[[Yoram Dinstein]], ''Anti-Semitism, Anti-Zionism and the United Nations'' in ''Israel's Yearbook of Human Rights'', Faculty of Law, Tel-Aviv University, vol.17, Martinus Nijhoff Publishers, 1987, p.16.</ref>\n\n==Contemporary definitions==\n\n===Non-position===\nNon-Zionism has also been defined in terms of a non-position on Zionism.  For example, Anthony Frosh on online Jewish magazine Galus Australis, has defined a non-Zionist Jews as a Jew \"who does not have any particular political relationship (positive or negative) with the State of Israel, or at least little more of a relationship than they would have with some other 3rd party state.\"[http://galusaustralis.com/2009/08/non-zionism-an-under-recognised-non-position/]\n\n=== Haredi non-Zionism===\nGenerally, those groups of [[Ashkenazi Jews|Ashkenazi]] (Western) [[Haredi Judaism|Haredi]] Jews who participate in the Israeli government but do not believe in the religious ideology of Zionism are known as \"non-Zionists\".  The most prominent non-Zionist Haredi group is [[World Agudath Israel|Agudath Israel]]. This is in contrast to the [[Religious Zionism|religious Zionist]] [[Mizrachi (political party)|Mizrachi party]] (which believes the State of Israel to be the beginning of the redemption); and also in contrast to the anti-Zionist Haredi groups, such as [[Satmar (Hasidic dynasty)|Satmar]] and the [[Edah HaChareidis|Edah Charedis]], that openly oppose Zionism and have little to no interaction with the State of Israel and no representation in its government. Unlike the older definition, many live in the State of Israel. They tend to be extremely pro-Israel politically, as can be seen in such publications as [[Mishpacha]] and [[Hamodia]]. [[Sephardi Jews|Sephardi]] Haredi Jews may refer to themselves as Zionist.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* Gideon Shimoni, ''From Anti-Zionism to Non-Zionism in Anglo Jewry, 1917-1937'', Jewish Journal of Sociology, 28 (1986), pp.19-48\n* Gideon Shimoni, ''The Non-Zionists in Anglo Jewry, 1937-1948''.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*Bennett Muraskin, ''[http://www.vcn.bc.ca/outlook/current_issue/May-Jun%2007/Anti-Zionism.pdf Anti-Zionism and Non-Zionism in Jewish Life\u2014Past and Present]'',\n{{Zionism}}\n[[Category:Political theories]]\n[[Category:Types of Zionism]]\n", "name_user": "Davide King", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eNon-position:ce ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-Zionism"}
{"title_page": "Troy Tulowitzki", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Troy Tulowitzki\n| image       = File:Troy Tulowitzki batting on August 19, 2015 (Cropped).jpg\n| image_size  = 250\n| caption     = Tulowitzki with the Blue Jays in 2015\n| position    = [[Shortstop]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1984|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Clara, California]]\n| bats        = Right\n| throws      = Right\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = August 30\n| debutyear   = 2006\n| debutteam   = Colorado Rockies\n| finalleague = MLB \n| finaldate   = April 3 \n| finalyear   = 2019\n| finalteam   = New York Yankees\n| statleague  = MLB\n| statyear    = \n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .290\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 225\n| stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 780\n| teams       = \n* [[Colorado Rockies]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2015}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2015}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|2019}})\n| awards      = \n* 5\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]], [[2011 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2011]], [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (2010, 2011)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2010, 2011)\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{bb|USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[World University Baseball Championship|2004 Tainan]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Troy Trevor Tulowitzki''' (born October 10, 1984), nicknamed \"'''Tulo'''\", is an American former [[professional baseball]] [[shortstop]], who played 13 seasons in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB), primarily with the [[Colorado Rockies]]. He also played for the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] and [[New York Yankees]].\n\nAfter playing [[college baseball]] for [[California State University, Long Beach]], the Rockies selected Tulowitzki with the seventh overall selection of the [[2005 MLB Draft]]. He made his MLB debut the following year. Tulowitzki is a five-time [[MLB All-Star Game|MLB All-Star]], a two-time [[Gold Glove Award]] winner, and a two-time [[Silver Slugger Award]] winner. The Rockies traded him to the Blue Jays in 2015. Tulowitzki missed most of the 2017 season and all of the 2018 season with injuries, and the Blue Jays released him after the 2018 season. In 2019, he signed with the Yankees, playing the first five games of the season before being sidelined with a calf strain; after experiencing setbacks, he announced his retirement from baseball in late July.\n\nTulowitzki's arm, range and instincts at shortstop were highly regarded. Furthermore, his size, ability and leadership skills garnered him comparisons to [[Cal Ripken Jr.]], [[Alex Rodriguez]], and [[Derek Jeter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlbplayers.mlb.com/pa/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071003&content_id=2247004&vkey=mlbpa_news&fext=.jsp|title=Troy Tulowitzki making his case|date=October 3, 2007|author=MLBPLAYERS.com|publisher=MLBPLAYERS.com|accessdate=July 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5726571,00.html |title=Tulowitzki rare mix of talent, leadership|accessdate=July 9, 2009|last=Fraley|first=Gerry|date=October 19, 2007|publisher=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|work=rockymountainnews.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410181727/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5726571,00.html| archivedate=April 10, 2008}}</ref> In spite of his talent, he fostered a reputation for being an injury-prone player, having played over 140 games in a season only three times and missing at least 30 games in several seasons due to various ailments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2655713-troy-tulowitzki-placed-on-10-day-dl-by-blue-jays-with-hamstring-injury|title=Troy Tulowitzki Placed on 10-Day DL by Blue Jays with Hamstring Injury|date=April 22, 2017|last=Wells|first=Adam|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|work=bleacherreport.com|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nTulowitzki graduated from [[Fremont High School (Sunnyvale, California)|Fremont High School]] in [[Sunnyvale, California]].<ref name=rockiesbio>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=453064 |title=Troy Tulowitzki: Biography and Career Highlights |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |publisher=[[MLB.com]]}}</ref> He earned four [[varsity letter]]s in baseball and two in basketball. He was twice named second team All-State in baseball, and was a three-time team [[most valuable player]] (MVP). As a junior, Tulowitzki had a [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .536. He also had a 15\u20131 [[win\u2013loss record (pitching)|win-loss record]] as a [[pitcher]]. In his senior year, he batted .519 with six [[home run]]s. In basketball, Tulowitzki won league MVP, and was second team All-State and team MVP, averaging 22.6 [[points per game]] during his senior year. He was named Fremont High Athlete of the Year in 2002.<ref name=rockiesbio />\n\nAfter high school, Tulowitzki enrolled at [[California State University, Long Beach]], where he played [[college baseball]] for the [[Long Beach State Dirtbags baseball|Long Beach State Dirtbags]] for three seasons. Tulowitzki had a .962 career [[fielding percentage]]. Offensively, in 155 career games, he had a batting average of .310, with 20 home runs, 117 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs), 37 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], and a .491 [[slugging percentage]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/teams/players/bio/?id=5709 |title=TSN profile |accessdate=July 9, 2009|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.longbeachstate.com/local/sid/features0708/tulowitzki100307.htm Tulo Had Success Written All Over]{{Dead link|date=July 2009}}</ref> He also accumulated 31 multi-hit games in his collegiate career. ''[[Baseball America]]'' rated him as having the top arm and as the best defensive shortstop in the [[Big West Conference]]. Tulowitzki was a two-time All-Big West selection (second team in 2003 and first team in 2004) and a two-time All-Regional Tournament selection, earning Most Outstanding Player (MOP) honors in 2004. In 2004, he was selected for the [[United States national baseball team|United States collegiate national team]] and helped lead Team USA to a gold medal in the [[World University Baseball Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Team USA Wins Gold at World University Baseball Championship |accessdate = August 7, 2011|publisher = Nebraska Huskers|url = http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=67795}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Colorado Rockies===\n====Minor League Baseball====\nThe [[Colorado Rockies]] chose Tulowitzki with the seventh overall pick in the first round of the [[2005 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref name=br>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/t/tulowtr01.shtml |title=Troy Tulowitzki Statistics|accessdate=July 9, 2009|publisher=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]}}</ref> He received a $2.3&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]] from the Rockies.<ref name=calledup/> He made his professional debut with the [[Modesto Nuts]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[California League]] in 2005, and batted .266 in 22 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://longbeachstate.com/news/2006/8/30/Tulowitzki_Called_up_to_the_Rockies.aspx |title=Tulowitzki Called up to the Rockies - Long Beach State University Athletics |publisher=Longbeachstate.com |date= |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> In 2006, Tulowitzki played for the [[Tulsa Drillers]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Texas League]]. He had a .291 batting average, 13 home runs, and 61 RBIs in 104 games. Though he had a knee injury in June, he appeared in the 2006 [[All-Star Futures Game]].<ref name=calledup>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/milb/news/tulowitzki-called-up-from-tulsa/c-125847 |title=Tulowitzki called up from Tulsa |publisher=MiLB.com |date=August 30, 2006 |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2006\u20132008====\nThe Rockies promoted Tulowitzki to the major leagues on August 30, 2006.<ref name=calledup/> He made his major league debut that day against the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=260830127 |title=New York Mets vs. Colorado Rockies \u2013 Recap|accessdate=July 9, 2009|author=DENVER (AP) |date=August 30, 2006 |publisher=[[ESPN]].com}}</ref> He had four at-bats and went hitless with three strikeouts. Tulowitzki made it to the big leagues after playing just 126 minor league games. He collected his first Major League hit, an [[infield single]] off [[\u00d3liver P\u00e9rez]] of the Mets, on August 31.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=260831127 |title=Francis a big hit at plate as Rockies avoid sweep by Mets |accessdate=July 9, 2009|author=DENVER (AP) |date=August 31, 2006 |publisher=[[ESPN]].com}}</ref> Tulowitzki hit his first MLB home run on September 4, off [[Woody Williams]] of the [[San Diego Padres]], in a 7\u20135 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=260904125 |title=Barfield helps Padres maintain wild-card lead, beat Rockies |accessdate=July 9, 2009|author=SAN DIEGO (AP) |date=September 4, 2006 |publisher=[[ESPN]].com}}</ref> He posted a .240 batting average with one home run and six RBIs in 25 games during the 2006 season.<ref name=br/>\n\nTulowitzki entered [[spring training]] prior to the [[2007 Colorado Rockies season|2007 season]] competing with incumbent Rockies [[shortstop]] [[Clint Barmes]] for the starting role. After a spring that saw Tulowitzki win the team's spring training MVP award, along with Barmes struggling offensively, Tulowitzki began the season as the Rockies' starting shortstop.<ref name=rockiesbio2007>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=453064&y=2007 |title=The Official Site of The Colorado Rockies: Team: Player Information : Biography and Career Highlights |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> On April 29, 2007, Tulowitzki turned the 13th [[unassisted triple play]] in MLB history, during a 9\u20137 home victory at [[Coors Field]] over the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1937361&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Tulowitzki turns unassisted triple play |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=270429127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Braves vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 April 29, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=April 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070511&content_id=1958203&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=The Official Site of The Colorado Rockies: News: Colorado Rockies News |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927221828/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070511&content_id=1958203&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archive-date=September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> \n\nAs a rookie, Tulowitzki established himself as a [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]]-caliber shortstop.<ref name=\"ESPNRookieTulo\">{{cite web |last1=Crasnick |first1=Jerry |title=Crasnick: Rookie Tulowitzki looks like a veteran |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=crasnick_jerry&id=3013854 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=27 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412124406/http://www.espn.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=crasnick_jerry&id=3013854 |archivedate=12 April 2019 |language=en |date=11 September 2007}}</ref><ref name=rmnrockiesdefense>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5723877,00.html|title=Rocky Mountain News - Denver and Colorado's reliable source for breaking news, sports and entertainment: Rockies & MLB|date=October 30, 2007|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030233649/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5723877,00.html|archivedate=October 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"MLBGoldenTulo\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=C.J. |title=Notes: Tulowitzki golden at short? {{!}} ColoradoRockies.com: News |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070915&content_id=2210586&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |website=mlb.com |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=27 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606025650/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070915&content_id=2210586&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=6 June 2011 |date=15 September 2007}}</ref> He led all [[MLB]] shortstops in fielding percentage (.987), putouts (262), total chances (834), assists (561), and double plays turned (114; two more than [[Jack Wilson (shortstop)|Jack Wilson]], in 233 more innings). He also ranked first in range factor (5.39) and second in zone rating (.866). Tulowitzki's .987 fielding percentage set an MLB-single season record by a rookie shortstop.<ref name=tulohouseholdname>{{cite web|url=http://longbeachstate.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/032008aad.html |title=Tulowitzki Turning into Household Name |publisher=Longbeachstate.cstv.com |date=March 14, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He was also a major contributor in the Rockies' MLB-record .98925 fielding percentage for one season.<ref name=rmnrockiesdefense /> [[Philadelphia Phillies]] shortstop [[Jimmy Rollins]] won the Gold Glove Award, despite the fact that Tulowitzki had a better fielding percentage (.987 to .985), zone rating, and range factor, and more total chances, putouts, and assists, and turned four more double plays, in {{frac|66|1|3}} fewer innings, than Rollins. They each had 11 errors, but Tulowitzki's came on 834 total chances, compared to Rollins' 717.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/stats/fielding?groupId=8&season=2007&seasonType=2&split=82&sortColumn=fieldingPct |title=2012 Regular Season MLB Baseball 1B Fielding Statistics \u2013 Major League Baseball \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki did, however, win the [[Fielding Bible Award]] at shortstop, which is awarded to the shortstop who a panel of national sports writers, scouts, and sports radio talk show hosts view as the best defensive shortstop in Major League Baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fieldingbible.com/ |title=Fielding Bible |publisher=Fielding Bible |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:TroyTulowitzki.JPG|thumb|200px|Troy Tulowitzki about to field his position (shortstop)]]\nTulowitzki was named the NL [[MLB Rookie of the Month Award|Rookie of the Month]] for August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070904&content_id=2189374&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Tulowitzki named Rookie of the Month |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> On September 10, 2007, Tulowitzki hit his 20th home run of the season, which set the record for most home runs in a single season by a National League rookie shortstop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070911&content_id=2201209&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=The Official Site of The Colorado Rockies: News: Colorado Rockies News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The previous record was 19, held by [[Ernie Banks]]. Tulowitzki hit his first career grand slam on September 29, 2007, in an 11\u20131 home win over the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], off of [[Dustin Nippert]].<ref name=rockiesbio2007 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=270929127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Diamondbacks vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 September 29, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=September 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He ended with 24 home runs on the season.\n\nIn the 2007 season, Tulowitzki ranked first among NL rookies in at bats (609), plate appearances (678), games (155), hits (177), doubles (33), runs (104), total bases (292), walks (57) and RBIs (99; two ahead of [[Ryan Braun]], in 158 more at bats than Braun). Tulowitzki's 99 RBIs led all National League shortstops (he was three short of a tie for the MLB lead, held by [[Detroit Tigers]] shortstop [[Carlos Guill\u00e9n]]). He set an MLB-single season record in RBIs for a rookie shortstop.<ref name=tulohouseholdname /> He finished second behind Braun in OBP (.359). He was third behind Braun and [[Hunter Pence]] in batting average (.291), slugging percentage (.479), OPS (.838) and triples (5). Tulowitzki was also third behind Braun and [[Chris Young (outfielder)|Chris Young]] in home runs (24) and extra base hits (62), and tied for ninth in stolen bases (7).{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\nTulowitzki tied Young, [[Rajai Davis]] and [[Norris Hopper]] for the lead among all NL rookies in caught stealing (6), was second to [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] in grounding into double plays (14, which was one more \u2013 with 158 more at bats \u2013 than third place Braun) and second behind Young in strikeouts (130; leading all NL shortstops). However, Tulowitzki had the third lowest strikeout ratio (21.3%) out of all rookies with at least 400 at-bats, behind [[Kevin Kouzmanoff]] (19.4%) and Pence (20.8%). He batted .320 with a .554 slugging percentage and 15 home runs at mile-high [[Coors Field]], but hit only .256 with a .393 slugging percentage and nine home runs in away games. However, one of the reasons for any substantial differences in home and road splits for Rockies batters is that they have to make adjustments in how they see pitches away from Coors Field \u2013 particularly breaking balls, such as sliders and curve balls \u2013 since those pitches act differently at Coors Field than on the road.<ref>{{cite web|author=Phil RogersArchive |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=rogers_phil&id=2046292 |title=ESPN \u2013 Coors Field a truly unique environment \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=April 26, 2005 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTeam veterans alerted Tulowitzki every time Braun, his chief rival for rookie of the year honors, hit a home run.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/rockies/2007-10-21-tulowitzki-cover_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Colorado rookie Tulowitzki provides veteran presence | first=Jorge L. | last=Ortiz | date=October 22, 2007 | accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki came in second in the race for National League [[Rookie of the Year (award)|Rookie of the Year]]. The award was voted on by 32 members of the [[Baseball Writers' Association of America]], two from each National League city. Braun beat Tulowitzki, 128 points to 126 points, which was the closest voting in the NL since the current system was adopted in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071112&content_id=2298624&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki also lost to Braun in the vote for the 2007 NL [[Sporting News Rookie of the Year Award|''Sporting News'' Rookie of the Year Award]], which was voted on by 488 major league players and 30 managers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071015&content_id=2267061&vkey=ps2007news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=290147 SportingNews.com \u2013 Your expert source for MLB Baseball stats, scores, standings, blogs and fantasy news from MLB Baseball columnists<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016084533/http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=290147 |date=October 16, 2007 }}</ref> He lost out to Braun for the 2007 [[Baseball America Rookie of the Year Award|''Baseball America'' Rookie of the Year Award]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Haudricourt |first=Tom |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/majors/features/265033.html |title=\"Record-Setting Bat Propels Braun,\" Baseball America, 10/17/07, accessed 10/18/07 |publisher=Baseballamerica.com |date=October 17, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> in the vote for the [[Players Choice Awards|2007 Players Choice NL Most Outstanding Rookie]] by their fellow major league players,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allamericanpatriots.com/48735746_sports_major_league_baseball_players_recognize_top_rookie_each_league |title=Major League Baseball Players Recognize Top Rookie in Each League |publisher=All American Patriots |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517030453/http://www.allamericanpatriots.com/48735746_sports_major_league_baseball_players_recognize_top_rookie_each_league |archivedate=May 17, 2011  }}</ref> Fans voted Tulowitzki the ''[[This Year in Baseball Awards|This Year in Baseball]]'' Rookie of the Year, with 27.6% of the vote, ahead of [[Boston Red Sox]] [[second baseman]] [[Dustin Pedroia]] (26.3%) and Braun (22.3%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2007/tyib/index.jsp |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: 2007 This Year in Baseball Awards |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki was selected to the [[Topps All-Star Rookie Rosters|2007 Topps Major League Rookie All-Star Team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071126&content_id=2307272&vkey=pr_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=\"Topps announces the 49th annual Topps Major League Rookie All-Star Team,\" KansasCity.Royals.mlb.com, 11/26/07, accessed 11/26/07 |publisher=Kansascity.royals.mlb.com |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511224852/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071126&content_id=2307272&vkey=pr_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archivedate=May 11, 2008  }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:TroyTulowitzki.jpg|thumb|200px| Tulowitzki catching a [[Glossary of baseball (P)#pop|pop-up]] in game four of the [[2007 World Series]]]]\n\nOn October 1, 2007, in the one-game [[2007 National League Wild Card tie-breaker game|Wild Card tie-breaker]] against the San Diego Padres, Tulowitzki went 4-for-7 with three extra-base hits and scored the tying run in the bottom of the 13th inning. The Rockies won the game, 9\u20138, and entered the playoffs as the NL [[wild card (sports)|wild card]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=271001127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Padres vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 1, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=October 1, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> They faced the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] in the [[2007 National League Division Series|National League Division Series]]. On October 4, 2007, in the second game of the series, Tulowitzki and [[left fielder]] [[Matt Holliday]] hit back-to-back first-pitch homers in the first inning to begin a 10\u20135 win, and the Rockies headed to Denver with a 2\u20130 lead in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=271004122 |title=ESPN \u2013 Rockies vs. Phillies \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 4, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=October 4, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The Rockies went on to complete a three-game sweep of the Phillies, and advanced to the [[2007 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]], in which they swept the Arizona Diamondbacks in four games. Colorado then played the [[Boston Red Sox]] in the [[2007 World Series|World Series]], which was the first ever World Series appearance in Rockies history. Boston swept Colorado in four games. Tulowitzki batted .195 in the postseason, with a .267 [[on-base percentage]] and 15 strikeouts in 41 at-bats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/7401470 |title=FOX Sports on MSN \u2013 Nine innings: Here's the dish on Cabrera |publisher=Msn.foxsports.com |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130090751/http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/7401470 |archivedate=November 30, 2007  }}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, [[2008 Colorado Rockies season|2008]], Tulowitzki signed a six-year, $31-million contract extension with the Rockies.<ref name=contractextension>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080120&content_id=2351593&vkey=hotstove2007&fext=.jsp |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The deal, which also included a club option for 2014, was the largest-ever contract for a player with less than two years experience until Ryan Braun signed an eight-year, $45-million contract extension with the Brewers on May 15, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080515&content_id=2705204&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&partnered=rss_mlb |title=Brewers sign Braun to eight-year deal |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2008, in a 3\u20132 road win over the [[San Francisco Giants]], Tulowitzki tore a left [[quadriceps tendon]] during a defensive play in the first inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080501&content_id=2623323&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Tulowitzki out at least until All-Star break |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927221905/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080501&content_id=2623323&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=September 27, 2011  }}</ref> He returned to the Rockies, starting at shortstop, on June 20, in a 7\u20132 home loss against the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=280620127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Mets vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 June 20, 2008 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=June 20, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> On July 5, 2008, Tulowitzki went back on the disabled list after cutting his right palm in the previous day's 18\u201317 home win over the [[Florida Marlins]]. The injury occurred in the bottom of the seventh inning when Tulowitzki slammed a maple bat into the ground in frustration. The incident took place after he was taken out of the game in that same inning; however, he noted that the frustration leading up to his injury wasn't due to being taken out, saying, \"I was a little bit frustrated, not at the move. If anything, I thought it was the right move. I came in the hallway, grabbed a bat, hit it on the ground and the bat exploded in my hand and cut open my palm running up to my index finger.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3474695 |title=ESPN \u2013 Tulowitzki placed on 15-day DL after cutting hand smashing bat \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 5, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The cut required 16 stitches, but no damage was done to any tendons or nerves. Tulowitzki returned to the Rockies lineup, starting at shortstop, on July 21, 2008, in a 16\u201310 home loss against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=280721127&action=playvideo&hcmp=motion |title=ESPN \u2013 Dodgers vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 July 21, 2008 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 21, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He recorded a career-high five hits during the game, as he went 5-for-5 with one RBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3499586 |title=ESPN \u2013 Tulowitzki has career-high five hits in Rockies' return \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 22, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> After returning on July 21 he has had six multi-hit games in his past eight games. In 38 games prior to July 21, Tulowitzki had six multi-hit games.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mid 5th |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/players/profile?playerId=28567 |title=ESPN \u2013 Troy Tulowitzki Stats, News, Photos \u2013 Colorado Rockies |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki ended the 2008 season with a .263 batting average, eight home runs, and 46 RBIs in 101 games.<ref name=br/>\n\n====2009\u20132011====\nOn August 10, 2009, Tulowitzki [[hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]] as part of an 11\u20135 home win over the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=290810127 |title=Chicago Cubs vs. Colorado Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 August 10, 2009 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=August 10, 2009 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He also had a career-high seven RBIs, which tied for the third-most RBIs in MLB history in a game for a player who hit for the cycle. Tulowitzki became the fifth Rockies player to hit for the cycle. He also was the second player in MLB history to hit for the cycle and record an unassisted triple play in a career. Tulowitzki hit a career-high 32 home runs during the season and had a .552 slugging percentage, both of which led all MLB shortstops. He was second in RBIs (92), triples (9), walks (73) and on-base plus slugging percentage (.930).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/touchingbase/2009/08/oh-boy-troy.html |location=New York |work=Daily News |title=Oh Boy, Troy! |first=Jesse |last=Spector |date=August 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813091239/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/touchingbase/2009/08/oh-boy-troy.html |archivedate=August 13, 2009  }}</ref> He finished fifth in voting by the [[Baseball Writers' Association of America]] for [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|National League MVP]].<ref name=2009mvpvoting>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091115&content_id=7669452 |title=Third time is charming for MVP Pujols &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:IMG 1880 Troy Tulowitzki.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Tulowitzki with the Rockies in 2010]]\nOn June 17, 2010, Tulowitzki fractured his wrist after being hit by a pitch from [[Minnesota Twins]] reliever [[Alex Burnett]]. He was placed on the disabled list the following day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100618&content_id=11317530&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Broken left wrist lands Tulowitzki on DL &#124; ColoradoRockies.com: News |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325042954/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100618&content_id=11317530&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=March 25, 2012  }}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 2010, Tulowitzki was one of two Rockies, along with starting pitcher [[Ubaldo Jim\u00e9nez]], selected as a [[National League]] All-Star to play in the [[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] at [[Angel Stadium of Anaheim]]. It was Tulowitzki's first All-Star appearance, but due to being on the disabled list since June 18 with a fractured wrist, he was replaced by [[New York Mets]] shortstop [[Jos\u00e9 Reyes (shortstop)|Jos\u00e9 Reyes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100704&content_id=11909034&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Jimenez, Tulowitzki named first-time All-Stars &#124; ColoradoRockies.com: News |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325042959/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100704&content_id=11909034&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=March 25, 2012  }}</ref> In September, Tulowitzki hit 14 home runs from September 3 through the 18th, garnering him back-to-back NL Player of the Week honors for September 6\u201312 and 13\u201319.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/rockies/2010/09/20/rockies-tulo-named-nl-player-of-the-week-again/4829/|title=Rockies' Troy Tulowitzki named NL player of the week -- again|work=On the Rox|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> He also earned his first National League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|Player of the Month]] award for his efforts during the month of September, in which he led all MLB players with 15 home runs, 40 RBI, 30 runs scored and an .800 slugging percentage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20101004&content_id=15412110&vkey=pr_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Tulowitzki, Lowe voted National League Player, Pitcher of the Month &#124; MLB.com: Official Info |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Only [[Babe Ruth]] had just as many or more home runs (17) and RBIs (43) during that month in MLB history.<ref name=silverslugger2010>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101111&content_id=16073124&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=CarGo, Tulo team up again, win Silver Sluggers &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki finished the 2010 season leading all MLB shortstops in home runs (27), RBIs (95), batting average (.315), on-base percentage (.381), slugging percentage (.568) and on-base plus slugging percentage (.949).<ref name=br/> He placed fifth in voting for [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|National League MVP]] for the second consecutive season.<ref name=2009mvpvoting /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101122&content_id=16171678&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Votto wins NL MVP by overwhelming margin &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki picked up his first [[Silver Slugger Award]] for his offensive prowess.<ref name=silverslugger2010 /> On the defensive side, he had the best fielding percentage (.984) and range factor (5.06) among all shortstops in the National League. He earned his second [[Fielding Bible Award]] and first [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]] at shortstop.<ref>[http://www.billjamesonline.net/fieldingbible/the-winners.asp] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100607130709/http://www.billjamesonline.net/fieldingbible/the-winners.asp |date=June 7, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5788835 |title=Scott Rolen wins Gold Glove in third different uniform \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=November 11, 2010 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He was also [[ESPN]]'s 2010 Web Gem champion.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fisher |first=John |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/11783/gold-glove-for-pujols-car-go-but-not-utley |title=Gold Glove for Pujols, CarGo but not Utley \u2013 Stats & Info Blog \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn November 29, 2010, Tulowitzki agreed to sign a six-year extension on top of the three years, with a fourth option year, remaining on his contract. The six-year extension was worth around $120 million, making it the second-largest contract ever signed by a Rockies player (behind Todd Helton's nine-year $141.5 million contract).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/baseball/mlb/11/29/rockies.tulowitzki/ | work=CNN | title=Rockies hand All-Star Tulowitzki six-year, $120 million extension | date=November 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki was elected by his fellow players as a National League reserve for the [[2011 MLB All-Star Game|2011 All-Star Game]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], but after an injury to starter [[Jos\u00e9 Reyes (shortstop)|Jos\u00e9 Reyes]] (who was chosen by fans), Tulowitzki became the NL's starting shortstop. He had one hit during the game, which was a single.{{cn|date=April 2018}} Tulowitzki won his second consecutive (third overall) [[Fielding Bible Award]], as the best fielding shortstop in MLB.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2011 Awards |url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |publisher=The Fielding Bible |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62sERzLeS?url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |archivedate=November 1, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> He also received his second consecutive [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]] and [[Silver Slugger Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111102&content_id=25873314&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=MLB's top offensive players earn Silver Slugger Awards &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111101&content_id=25865014&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Nine first-time winners highlight Gold Gloves &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u20132015====\nOn April 1, 2012, during a spring training game against the [[Cleveland Indians]], Tulowitzki was hit by a pitch on the arm by former teammate [[Ubaldo Jim\u00e9nez]]. Both Tulowitzki and Jim\u00e9nez came close to each other while the benches cleared. Jim\u00e9nez received a five-game suspension and an undisclosed fine.\nAs the season progressed, Tulowitzki required surgery on his left groin, which ended his season. The injury happened on May 30, during a doubleheader with the [[Houston Astros]].{{cn|date=January 2019}} He was limited to 47 games, in which he batted .287 with eight home runs and 27 RBIs.<ref name=br/>\n\nOn June 13, 2013, Tulowitzki suffered a fractured right rib in a 5\u20134 loss to the Nationals. He was placed on the 15-day disabled list and missed 25 games. Despite the injury, Tulowitzki was selected for the 2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game. Teammates [[Carlos Gonz\u00e1lez (baseball)|Carlos Gonz\u00e1lez]] and [[Michael Cuddyer]] were also selected, and all three players were in the starting lineup for the National League. Tulowitzki hit .312 in 126 games in 2013, with 25 home runs and 82 RBIs.<ref name=br/>\n\nTulowitzki started 2014 by batting .364 in April with seven home runs, nine doubles, and 22 RBIs. His hot start earned him the [[NL Player of the Month]] honors for April. On May 3, Tulowitzki singled for his 1,000th career hit in a game against the [[New York Mets]]. He injured his left hip during a July 20 game, and  underwent labral repair surgery on August 15, which ended his season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Silva|first1=Drew|title=Troy Tulowitzki to undergo season-ending hip surgery|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2014/08/13/troy-tulowitzki-to-undergo-season-ending-hip-surgery/|work=NBC Sports|date=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Tulowitzki finished the campaign with a .340 batting average in 91 games played. Despite his injury shortened season, he hit 21 home runs and 58 RBI.<ref name=br/>\n\nTulowitzki made his fifth All-Star team in 2015 as a replacement for the injured [[Dee Gordon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/07/11/troy-tulowitzki-replaces-dee-gordon-on-the-nl-all-star-team/|title=Troy Tulowitzki replaces Dee Gordon on the NL All-Star team - HardballTalk|work=nbcsports.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> He batted .300 with 12 home runs and 53 RBIs in 87 games with the Rockies before being traded.<ref name=br/>\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays===\n====Rest of 2015====\n[[File:Tulo_Swinging_2016.jpg|thumb|right|270px|Tulowitzki about to hit a pitch during Spring Training 2016.]]\nOn July 28, 2015, Tulowitzki was traded, along with teammate [[LaTroy Hawkins]], to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] in exchange for [[Jos\u00e9 Reyes (shortstop)|Jos\u00e9 Reyes]], [[Jeff Hoffman]], [[Miguel Castro]] and [[Jes\u00fas Tinoco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/139167952/rockies-trade-troy-tulowitzki-to-blue-jays|title=Tulo Toronto-bound; Rockies get Reyes|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> Upon being informed of the trade during the middle of the ninth inning of a game at the [[Chicago Cubs]], as Blue Jays and Rockies management had kept negotiations secret from the media, Tulowitzki reportedly yelled at Rockies general manager [[Jeff Bridich]] and vowed never to speak to him or other members of the Rockies front office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/bob-nightengale/2016/02/29/troy-tulowitzki-still-seething-over-rockie-exit-denver/81085588/|title=Troy Tulowitzki still seething over Rockie exit from Denver|last=Nightengale|first=Bob|work=usatoday.com|date=February 29, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Tulowitzki expressed mixed emotions about the trade, but stated, \"I get the chance to play for a contender, and maybe this will revive my career a little bit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/13334658/troy-tulowitzki-says-was-blindsided-trade-colorado-rockies-toronto-blue-jays|title=Troy Tulowitzki says he was \"shocked\" by trade to Blue Jays|last=Gregorson|first=Derrick|work=ESPN.com|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> \n\nTulowitzki made his debut with the Blue Jays on July 29, and went 3-for-5 with a home run, two doubles, three RBIs and three runs scored.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rutsey|first1=Mike|title=Blue Jays' Tulowitzki special in debut, a romp over Phillies|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/07/29/blue-jays-tulowitzki-special-in-debut-a-romp-over-phillies|accessdate=July 29, 2015|publisher=Toronto Sun|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> During a game against the [[New York Yankees]] on September 12, Tulowitzki collided with teammate [[Kevin Pillar]] while backpedaling to catch a fly ball in centerfield, and had to leave the game. He was expected to be out for a minimum of 2-3 weeks due to a cracked shoulder blade.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chisholm|first1=Gregor|title=Tentative timetable has Tulo out 2-3 weeks|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/149078024/troy-tulowitzki-could-return-by-end-of-season|work=MLB.com|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> Tulowitzki returned to the lineup shortly before the end of the season after missing 18 games, and in total, appeared in 41 games for the Blue Jays in 2015, batting .239 with five home runs and 17 RBIs.<ref name=br/> The Blue Jays had a record of 50-51 and stood at fourth place in the AL East, but Tulowitzki's arrival helped the Jays go 43-18 for the rest of the regular season to capture the AL East Division title and earn their first playoff berth since 1993.<ref>[https://www.cp24.com/sports/newly-retired-shortstop-tulowitzki-reflects-on-time-with-blue-jays-1.4528408]</ref> \n\nTulowitzki played in all 5 games of the [[2015 American League Division Series]], batting .095 with one home run and four RBIs.<ref name=br/> In the third game of the [[2015 American League Championship Series]], Tulowitzki hit a three-run home run and was later ejected, becoming the first American League player to be ejected from a postseason game since [[Dwight Gooden]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2286829/blue-jays-troy-tulowitzki-ejected-from-game-3-of-alcs/|title=Blue Jays\u2019 Troy Tulowitzki ejected from Game 3 of ALCS|last=Coutu|first=Melissa|work=globalnews.ca|date=October 19, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref> The Blue Jays won the game, 11\u20138.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/154967532/blue-jays-beat-royals-in-game-3-of-alcs|title=Blue Jays outslug KC to trim ALCS deficit|last1=Chisholm|first1=Gregor|last2=Flanagan|first2=Jeffrey|work=MLB.com|date=October 20, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref> The Jays advanced to the [[2015 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]], which was won by the [[Kansas City Royals]] in six games.\n\n====2016&ndash;2018====\nOn May 13, 2016, Tulowitzki hit his 200th career home run in a win over the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/178003026/ra-dickey-leads-blue-jays-over-rangers|title=Blue Jays handle Texas with R.A. dealing|last1=Sullivan|first1=T.R.|last2=Chisholm|first2=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 13, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> On May 28, he was placed on the 15-day disabled list due to a right quad strain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-place-tulowitzki-15-day-dl-activate-loup/|title=Blue Jays place Tulowitzki on 15-day DL, activate Loup|last=Zwelling|first=Arden|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=May 28, 2016|accessdate=May 29, 2016}}</ref> He was reactivated on June 18, having missed 20 games due to the injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2016/6/18/11969012/troy-tulowitzki-activated-andy-burns-sent-down |title=Troy Tulowitzki activated, Andy Burns sent down |first=Tom |last=Dakers |date=June 18, 2016 |accessdate=June 18, 2016 |work=Bluebird Banter}}</ref> Tulowitzki struggled in 2016, batting a career low .254 in 131 games, though he also hit 24 home runs with 79 RBIs.\n\nTulowitzki was placed on the 10-day disabled list on April 22, 2017 after suffering a hamstring injury.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2655713-troy-tulowitzki-placed-on-10-day-dl-by-blue-jays-with-hamstring-injury|title=Troy Tulowitzki Placed on 10-Day DL by Blue Jays with Hamstring Injury|last=Wells|first=Adam|work=Bleacher Report|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> He returned to the lineup on May 26 after missing 31 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=tulowtr01&t=b&year=2017|title=Troy Tulowitzki 2017 Batting Gamelogs|website=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> On July 29, Tulowitzki was placed back on the disabled list with a sprained right ankle, which he injured running to first base.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2707397-troy-tulowitzki-placed-on-10-day-dl-with-ankle-injury|title=Troy Tulowitzki Placed on 10-Day DL with Ankle Injury|last=Wells|first=Adam|work=Bleacher Report|access-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref> He was later diagnosed with ligament damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/blue-jays-troy-tulowitzki-diagnosed-with-ligament-damage-to-ankle/|title=Blue Jays' Troy Tulowitzki: Diagnosed with ligament damage to ankle|work=CBSSports.com|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> On August 9, he was moved to the 60-day disabled list, ruling him out for the season. In 66 games, Tulowitzki hit .249 with seven home runs and 26 RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-transfer-troy-tulowitzki-60-day-dl/|title=Blue Jays transfer Troy Tulowitzki to 60-day DL|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=August 9, 2017|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2018 spring training, it was announced that Tulowitzki had a [[bone spur]] in his right ankle, and that he would miss the start of the [[Grapefruit League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/blue-jays-troy-tulowitzki-dealing-with-bone-spur/|title=Blue Jays' Troy Tulowitzki: Dealing with bone spur|work=cbssports.com|date=February 14, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref> On March 4, [[John Gibbons]] stated Tulowitzki was unlikely to be ready for [[Opening Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-tulowitzki-not-expected-ready-opening-day/|title=Blue Jays\u2019 Tulowitzki not expected to be ready for opening day|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=March 4, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref> Tulowitzki did not appear in any spring training games, and was placed on the 60-day disabled list to begin the year. On March 30, it was announced that his bone spurs required surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/injured-blue-jays-shortstop-troy-tulowitzki-surgery-monday/|title=Injured Blue Jays shortstop Troy Tulowitzki to have surgery Monday|last=Loung|first=Steven|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=March 30, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He missed the entire 2018 season. On December 11, 2018, Tulowitzki was released by the Blue Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-release-shortstop-troy-tulowitzki/ |title=Blue Jays release shortstop Troy Tulowitzki |publisher=Sportsnet.ca |date=December 11, 2018 |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref> The Blue Jays still owe $38&nbsp;million on the two remaining years of Tulowitzki's contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8e5fc46ce7344aba845b83283575b34e|title=Troy Tulowitzki released by Blue Jays, owed $38 million|date=December 12, 2018|website=AP NEWS|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===New York Yankees===\nOn January 4, 2019, Tulowitzki signed a one year contract with the [[New York Yankees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25664749/yankees-bolster-infield-agree-veteran-ss-troy-tulowitzki |title=Yankees bolster infield, agree with veteran SS Troy Tulowitzki |publisher=Espn.com |date=2019-01-04 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> They paid him the major league minimum salary of $555,000 and the contract included a no-trade clause.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Dan |url=https://nypost.com/2019/01/06/the-concession-that-brought-troy-tulowitzki-to-the-yankees/ |title=The concession that brought Troy Tulowitzki to the Yankees |publisher=Nypost.com |date=2019-01-06 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> He won the starting shortstop job with [[Didi Gregorius]] injured for the start of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25685967/troy-tulowitzki-new-york-yankees-opportunity-earn-starting-shortstop-job-gm-brian-cashman-says |title=Troy Tulowitzki of New York Yankees will have opportunity to earn starting shortstop job, GM Brian Cashman says |publisher=Espn.com |date=2019-01-07 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> \n\nHe hit his first home run as a yankee and also his last professional home run, a solo shot at bottom 9-inning, against [[Baltimore Orioles]]' and former yankees left-handed reliever [[Richard Bleier]] on March 30, 2019.\n\nAfter playing in five games to begin the season, he went on the IL with a left calf strain.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoch |first=Bryan |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/a-look-at-the-yankees-injury-timetables |title=A look at the Yankees' injury timetables |publisher=MLB.com |date=2019-06-29 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> On June 7, he was transferred to the 60-day injured list.\n\nOn July 25, Tulowitzki announced his retirement from Major League Baseball through a statement by the Yankees.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoch |first=Bryan |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/troy-tulowitzki-retires |title=Troy Tulowitzki retires |publisher=MLB.com |date=2018-05-24 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nUpon retiring as a player, Tulowitzki was hired by the [[Texas Longhorns baseball|Texas Longhorns]] as an assistant coach.<ref>https://www.si.com/mlb/2019/07/25/troy-tulowitzki-retires-yankees-rockies-shortstop</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTulowitzki is of Polish descent,<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown |first=David |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/blog/big_league_stew/post/Answer-Man-Troy-Tulowitzki-talks-brackets-Dirt?urn=mlb-228829 |title=Answer Man: Troy Tulowitzki talks brackets, Dirtbags and mullets \u2013 Big League Stew \u2013 MLB Blog \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> and was born in [[Santa Clara, California]].<ref> {{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/player/453064/troy-tulowitzki|title=Troy Tulowitzki Stats, Fantasy & News|work=MLB.com|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref> Tulowitzki attended [[Fremont High School (Sunnyvale, California)|Fremont High School]] in Sunnyvale, California. He played Little League baseball with Sunnyvale National. Tulowitzki has a sister, Tiffany, who plays softball, and a brother, Tyler, who played baseball for [[San Francisco State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfstategators.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=1199 |title=San Francisco State University Athletics \u2013 2012 Baseball Roster |publisher=Sfstategators.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki's favorite player growing up was [[Derek Jeter]]. His jersey number with the Rockies and Blue Jays was No. 2, due to his admiration of Jeter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_5572993 | work=Denver Post | first=Troy E. | last=Renck | title=Shortstop on way to stardom | date=April 2, 2007}}</ref> In a television interview with [[ESPN]], Tulowitzki stated that his favorite team growing up was the [[Oakland Athletics]] and that his favorite musical artist is [[Jay-Z]].{{cn|date=July 2015}}\n\nIn November 2009, Tulowitzki married his high school sweetheart, Danyll Gammon, in [[Portola Valley, California]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/search/ci_14321332 | work=Denver Post | first=Troy E. | last=Renck | title=Rockies' star Tulowitzki armed with better sense of priorities | date=February 3, 2010}}</ref> In January 2014, the Tulowitzkis became parents to a son, Taz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_25449515/mark-kiszla-face-colorado-rockies-now-father-too|title=Kiszla: Troy Tulowitzki, face of the Rockies, now a father too|work=denverpost.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 5\u00d7 [[National League]] All-Star selection ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]], [[2011 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2011]], [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]], [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2014]], [[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* 2\u00d7 National League [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]]: Shortstop (2010, 2011)\n* 2\u00d7 National League [[Silver Slugger Award]]: Shortstop (2010, 2011)\n* National League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|Player of the Month]] (September 2010)\n* 4\u00d7 National League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|Player of the Week]] (August 6\u201312, 2007, September 14\u201320, 2009, September 6\u201312, 2010, September 13\u201319, 2010)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Fielding Bible Award]]: Shortstop (2007, 2010, 2011)\n* [[This Year in Baseball Awards|This Year in Baseball]] Rookie of the Year (2007)\n* [[Topps All-Star Rookie Rosters|Topps Major League Rookie All-Star Team]]: Shortstop (2007)\n* National League [[MLB Rookie of the Month Award|Rookie of the Month]] (August 2007)\n* Colorado Rockies Minor League Player of the Year (2006)\n* [[All-Star Futures Game]] (2006)<ref name=calledup/>\n* [[Big West Conference]] All-Star: Shortstop (2004, 2005)\n* [[Palo Alto]] Regional MVP: [[2004 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Baseball}}\n* [[List of largest sports contracts]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players to hit for the cycle]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=453064|espn=28567|br=t/tulowtr01|fangraphs=3531|brm=tulowi001tro|retro=T/Ptulot001}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-ach}}}}\n{{succession box|before = [[Francisco Liriano]] |title = [[This Year in Baseball Awards|This Year in Baseball Rookie of the Year]]|years = 2007|after = [[Evan Longoria]]}}\n{{succession box| before = [[Ryan Braun]] | title = [[MLB Rookie of the Month Award|National League Rookie of the Month]]|years = August 2007|after = [[James Loney (baseball)|James Loney]]}}\n{{Succession box|before = [[Melky Cabrera]] | title = [[Hitting for the cycle]]| years = August 10, 2009 | after = [[F\u00e9lix Pie]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{This Year in Baseball Rookie of the Year Award}}\n{{NL SS Gold Glove Award}}\n{{NL SS Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{SS Fielding Bible Award}}\n{{2005 MLB Draft}}\n{{Colorado Rockies first-round draft picks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tulowitzki, Troy}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sunnyvale, California]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:National League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:All-Star Futures Game players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball shortstops]]\n[[Category:Colorado Rockies players]]\n[[Category:Toronto Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:New York Yankees players]]\n[[Category:Long Beach State Dirtbags baseball players]]\n[[Category:Modesto Nuts players]]\n[[Category:Tulsa Drillers players]]\n[[Category:Grand Canyon Rafters players]]\n[[Category:Colorado Springs Sky Sox players]]\n[[Category:Dunedin Blue Jays players]]\n[[Category:People from Santa Clara, California]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns baseball coaches]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Troy Tulowitzki\n| image       = File:Troy Tulowitzki batting on August 19, 2015 (Cropped).jpg\n| image_size  = 250\n| caption     = Tulowitzki with the Blue Jays in 2015\n| position    = [[Shortstop]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1984|10|10}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Clara, California]]\n| bats        = Right\n| throws      = Right\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = August 30\n| debutyear   = 2006\n| debutteam   = Colorado Rockies\n| finalleague = MLB \n| finaldate   = April 3 \n| finalyear   = 2019\n| finalteam   = New York Yankees\n| statleague  = MLB\n| statyear    = \n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .290\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 225\n| stat3label  = [[Run batted in|Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 780\n| teams       = \n* [[Colorado Rockies]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2015}})\n* [[Toronto Blue Jays]] ({{mlby|2015}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[New York Yankees]] ({{mlby|2019}})\n| awards      = \n* 5\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]], [[2011 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2011]], [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]]\u2013[[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Gold Glove Award]] (2010, 2011)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2010, 2011)\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{bb|USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World University Baseball Championship|World University Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[World University Baseball Championship|2004 Tainan]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Troy Trevor Tulowitzki''' (born October 10, 1984), nicknamed \"'''Tulo'''\", is an American former [[professional baseball]] [[shortstop]], who played 13 seasons in [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB), primarily with the [[Colorado Rockies]]. He also played for the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] and [[New York Yankees]].\n\nAfter playing [[college baseball]] for [[California State University, Long Beach]], the Rockies selected Tulowitzki with the seventh overall selection of the [[2005 MLB Draft]]. He made his MLB debut the following year. Tulowitzki is a five-time [[MLB All-Star Game|MLB All-Star]], a two-time [[Gold Glove Award]] winner, and a two-time [[Silver Slugger Award]] winner. The Rockies traded him to the Blue Jays in 2015. Tulowitzki missed most of the 2017 season and all of the 2018 season with injuries, and the Blue Jays released him after the 2018 season. In 2019, he signed with the Yankees, playing the first five games of the season before being sidelined with a calf strain; after experiencing setbacks, he announced his retirement from baseball in late July.\n\nTulowitzki's arm, range and instincts at shortstop were highly regarded. Furthermore, his size, ability and leadership skills garnered him comparisons to [[Cal Ripken Jr.]], [[Alex Rodriguez]], and [[Derek Jeter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlbplayers.mlb.com/pa/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071003&content_id=2247004&vkey=mlbpa_news&fext=.jsp|title=Troy Tulowitzki making his case|date=October 3, 2007|author=MLBPLAYERS.com|publisher=MLBPLAYERS.com|accessdate=July 9, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5726571,00.html |title=Tulowitzki rare mix of talent, leadership|accessdate=July 9, 2009|last=Fraley|first=Gerry|date=October 19, 2007|publisher=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|work=rockymountainnews.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080410181727/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5726571,00.html| archivedate=April 10, 2008}}</ref> In spite of his talent, he fostered a reputation for being an injury-prone player, having played over 140 games in a season only three times and missing at least 30 games in several seasons due to various ailments.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2655713-troy-tulowitzki-placed-on-10-day-dl-by-blue-jays-with-hamstring-injury|title=Troy Tulowitzki Placed on 10-Day DL by Blue Jays with Hamstring Injury|date=April 22, 2017|last=Wells|first=Adam|publisher=[[Bleacher Report]]|work=bleacherreport.com|accessdate=July 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Amateur career==\nTulowitzki graduated from [[Fremont High School (Sunnyvale, California)|Fremont High School]] in [[Sunnyvale, California]].<ref name=rockiesbio>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=453064 |title=Troy Tulowitzki: Biography and Career Highlights |accessdate=July 9, 2009 |publisher=[[MLB.com]]}}</ref> He earned four [[varsity letter]]s in baseball and two in basketball. He was twice named second team All-State in baseball, and was a three-time team [[most valuable player]] (MVP). As a junior, Tulowitzki had a [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .536. He also had a 15\u20131 [[win\u2013loss record (pitching)|win-loss record]] as a [[pitcher]]. In his senior year, he batted .519 with six [[home run]]s. In basketball, Tulowitzki won league MVP, and was second team All-State and team MVP, averaging 22.6 [[points per game]] during his senior year. He was named Fremont High Athlete of the Year in 2002.<ref name=rockiesbio />\n\nAfter high school, Tulowitzki enrolled at [[California State University, Long Beach]], where he played [[college baseball]] for the [[Long Beach State Dirtbags baseball|Long Beach State Dirtbags]] for three seasons. Tulowitzki had a .962 career [[fielding percentage]]. Offensively, in 155 career games, he had a batting average of .310, with 20 home runs, 117 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs), 37 [[double (baseball)|doubles]], and a .491 [[slugging percentage]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tsn.ca/mlb/teams/players/bio/?id=5709 |title=TSN profile |accessdate=July 9, 2009|publisher=[[The Sports Network]]}}</ref><ref>[http://www.longbeachstate.com/local/sid/features0708/tulowitzki100307.htm Tulo Had Success Written All Over]{{Dead link|date=July 2009}}</ref> He also accumulated 31 multi-hit games in his collegiate career. ''[[Baseball America]]'' rated him as having the top arm and as the best defensive shortstop in the [[Big West Conference]]. Tulowitzki was a two-time All-Big West selection (second team in 2003 and first team in 2004) and a two-time All-Regional Tournament selection, earning Most Outstanding Player (MOP) honors in 2004. In 2004, he was selected for the [[United States national baseball team|United States collegiate national team]] and helped lead Team USA to a gold medal in the [[World University Baseball Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|title = Team USA Wins Gold at World University Baseball Championship |accessdate = August 7, 2011|publisher = Nebraska Huskers|url = http://www.huskers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=100&ATCLID=67795}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n===Colorado Rockies===\n====Minor League Baseball====\nThe [[Colorado Rockies]] chose Tulowitzki with the seventh overall pick in the first round of the [[2005 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref name=br>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/t/tulowtr01.shtml |title=Troy Tulowitzki Statistics|accessdate=July 9, 2009|publisher=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]}}</ref> He received a $2.3&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]] from the Rockies.<ref name=calledup/> He made his professional debut with the [[Modesto Nuts]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[California League]] in 2005, and batted .266 in 22 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://longbeachstate.com/news/2006/8/30/Tulowitzki_Called_up_to_the_Rockies.aspx |title=Tulowitzki Called up to the Rockies - Long Beach State University Athletics |publisher=Longbeachstate.com |date= |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> In 2006, Tulowitzki played for the [[Tulsa Drillers]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Texas League]]. He had a .291 batting average, 13 home runs, and 61 RBIs in 104 games. Though he had a knee injury in June, he appeared in the 2006 [[All-Star Futures Game]].<ref name=calledup>{{cite web|url=https://www.milb.com/milb/news/tulowitzki-called-up-from-tulsa/c-125847 |title=Tulowitzki called up from Tulsa |publisher=MiLB.com |date=August 30, 2006 |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====2006\u20132008====\nThe Rockies promoted Tulowitzki to the major leagues on August 30, 2006.<ref name=calledup/> He made his major league debut that day against the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=260830127 |title=New York Mets vs. Colorado Rockies \u2013 Recap|accessdate=July 9, 2009|author=DENVER (AP) |date=August 30, 2006 |publisher=[[ESPN]].com}}</ref> He had four at-bats and went hitless with three strikeouts. Tulowitzki made it to the big leagues after playing just 126 minor league games. He collected his first Major League hit, an [[infield single]] off [[\u00d3liver P\u00e9rez]] of the Mets, on August 31.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=260831127 |title=Francis a big hit at plate as Rockies avoid sweep by Mets |accessdate=July 9, 2009|author=DENVER (AP) |date=August 31, 2006 |publisher=[[ESPN]].com}}</ref> Tulowitzki hit his first MLB home run on September 4, off [[Woody Williams]] of the [[San Diego Padres]], in a 7\u20135 loss.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=260904125 |title=Barfield helps Padres maintain wild-card lead, beat Rockies |accessdate=July 9, 2009|author=SAN DIEGO (AP) |date=September 4, 2006 |publisher=[[ESPN]].com}}</ref> He posted a .240 batting average with one home run and six RBIs in 25 games during the 2006 season.<ref name=br/>\n\nTulowitzki entered [[spring training]] prior to the [[2007 Colorado Rockies season|2007 season]] competing with incumbent Rockies [[shortstop]] [[Clint Barmes]] for the starting role. After a spring that saw Tulowitzki win the team's spring training MVP award, along with Barmes struggling offensively, Tulowitzki began the season as the Rockies' starting shortstop.<ref name=rockiesbio2007>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player_career.jsp?player_id=453064&y=2007 |title=The Official Site of The Colorado Rockies: Team: Player Information : Biography and Career Highlights |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> On April 29, 2007, Tulowitzki turned the 13th [[unassisted triple play]] in MLB history, during a 9\u20137 home victory at [[Coors Field]] over the [[Atlanta Braves]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070429&content_id=1937361&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Tulowitzki turns unassisted triple play |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=270429127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Braves vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 April 29, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=April 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070511&content_id=1958203&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=The Official Site of The Colorado Rockies: News: Colorado Rockies News |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927221828/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070511&content_id=1958203&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archive-date=September 27, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> \n\nAs a rookie, Tulowitzki established himself as a [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]]-caliber shortstop.<ref name=\"ESPNRookieTulo\">{{cite web |last1=Crasnick |first1=Jerry |title=Crasnick: Rookie Tulowitzki looks like a veteran |url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=crasnick_jerry&id=3013854 |website=ESPN.com |accessdate=27 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412124406/http://www.espn.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=crasnick_jerry&id=3013854 |archivedate=12 April 2019 |language=en |date=11 September 2007}}</ref><ref name=rmnrockiesdefense>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5723877,00.html|title=Rocky Mountain News - Denver and Colorado's reliable source for breaking news, sports and entertainment: Rockies & MLB|date=October 30, 2007|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071030233649/http://www.rockymountainnews.com/drmn/mlb/article/0,2777,DRMN_23924_5723877,00.html|archivedate=October 30, 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"MLBGoldenTulo\">{{cite web |last1=Moore |first1=C.J. |title=Notes: Tulowitzki golden at short? {{!}} ColoradoRockies.com: News |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070915&content_id=2210586&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |website=mlb.com |publisher=Major League Baseball |accessdate=27 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606025650/http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070915&content_id=2210586&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=6 June 2011 |date=15 September 2007}}</ref> He led all [[MLB]] shortstops in fielding percentage (.987), putouts (262), total chances (834), assists (561), and double plays turned (114; two more than [[Jack Wilson (shortstop)|Jack Wilson]], in 233 more innings). He also ranked first in range factor (5.39) and second in zone rating (.866). Tulowitzki's .987 fielding percentage set an MLB-single season record by a rookie shortstop.<ref name=tulohouseholdname>{{cite web|url=http://longbeachstate.cstv.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/032008aad.html |title=Tulowitzki Turning into Household Name |publisher=Longbeachstate.cstv.com |date=March 14, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He was also a major contributor in the Rockies' MLB-record .98925 fielding percentage for one season.<ref name=rmnrockiesdefense /> [[Philadelphia Phillies]] shortstop [[Jimmy Rollins]] won the Gold Glove Award, despite the fact that Tulowitzki had a better fielding percentage (.987 to .985), zone rating, and range factor, and more total chances, putouts, and assists, and turned four more double plays, in {{frac|66|1|3}} fewer innings, than Rollins. They each had 11 errors, but Tulowitzki's came on 834 total chances, compared to Rollins' 717.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/stats/fielding?groupId=8&season=2007&seasonType=2&split=82&sortColumn=fieldingPct |title=2012 Regular Season MLB Baseball 1B Fielding Statistics \u2013 Major League Baseball \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki did, however, win the [[Fielding Bible Award]] at shortstop, which is awarded to the shortstop who a panel of national sports writers, scouts, and sports radio talk show hosts view as the best defensive shortstop in Major League Baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fieldingbible.com/ |title=Fielding Bible |publisher=Fielding Bible |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:TroyTulowitzki.JPG|thumb|200px|Troy Tulowitzki about to field his position (shortstop)]]\nTulowitzki was named the NL [[MLB Rookie of the Month Award|Rookie of the Month]] for August.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070904&content_id=2189374&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Tulowitzki named Rookie of the Month |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> On September 10, 2007, Tulowitzki hit his 20th home run of the season, which set the record for most home runs in a single season by a National League rookie shortstop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070911&content_id=2201209&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=The Official Site of The Colorado Rockies: News: Colorado Rockies News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The previous record was 19, held by [[Ernie Banks]]. Tulowitzki hit his first career grand slam on September 29, 2007, in an 11\u20131 home win over the [[Arizona Diamondbacks]], off of [[Dustin Nippert]].<ref name=rockiesbio2007 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=270929127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Diamondbacks vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 September 29, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=September 29, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He ended with 24 home runs on the season.\n\nIn the 2007 season, Tulowitzki ranked first among NL rookies in at bats (609), plate appearances (678), games (155), hits (177), doubles (33), runs (104), total bases (292), walks (57) and RBIs (99; two ahead of [[Ryan Braun]], in 158 more at bats than Braun). Tulowitzki's 99 RBIs led all National League shortstops (he was three short of a tie for the MLB lead, held by [[Detroit Tigers]] shortstop [[Carlos Guill\u00e9n]]). He set an MLB-single season record in RBIs for a rookie shortstop.<ref name=tulohouseholdname /> He finished second behind Braun in OBP (.359). He was third behind Braun and [[Hunter Pence]] in batting average (.291), slugging percentage (.479), OPS (.838) and triples (5). Tulowitzki was also third behind Braun and [[Chris Young (outfielder)|Chris Young]] in home runs (24) and extra base hits (62), and tied for ninth in stolen bases (7).{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\nTulowitzki tied Young, [[Rajai Davis]] and [[Norris Hopper]] for the lead among all NL rookies in caught stealing (6), was second to [[Carlos Ruiz (baseball)|Carlos Ruiz]] in grounding into double plays (14, which was one more \u2013 with 158 more at bats \u2013 than third place Braun) and second behind Young in strikeouts (130; leading all NL shortstops). However, Tulowitzki had the third lowest strikeout ratio (21.3%) out of all rookies with at least 400 at-bats, behind [[Kevin Kouzmanoff]] (19.4%) and Pence (20.8%). He batted .320 with a .554 slugging percentage and 15 home runs at mile-high [[Coors Field]], but hit only .256 with a .393 slugging percentage and nine home runs in away games. However, one of the reasons for any substantial differences in home and road splits for Rockies batters is that they have to make adjustments in how they see pitches away from Coors Field \u2013 particularly breaking balls, such as sliders and curve balls \u2013 since those pitches act differently at Coors Field than on the road.<ref>{{cite web|author=Phil RogersArchive |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/columns/story?columnist=rogers_phil&id=2046292 |title=ESPN \u2013 Coors Field a truly unique environment \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=April 26, 2005 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTeam veterans alerted Tulowitzki every time Braun, his chief rival for rookie of the year honors, hit a home run.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite news| url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/rockies/2007-10-21-tulowitzki-cover_N.htm | work=USA Today | title=Colorado rookie Tulowitzki provides veteran presence | first=Jorge L. | last=Ortiz | date=October 22, 2007 | accessdate=May 26, 2010}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki came in second in the race for National League [[Rookie of the Year (award)|Rookie of the Year]]. The award was voted on by 32 members of the [[Baseball Writers' Association of America]], two from each National League city. Braun beat Tulowitzki, 128 points to 126 points, which was the closest voting in the NL since the current system was adopted in 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071112&content_id=2298624&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki also lost to Braun in the vote for the 2007 NL [[Sporting News Rookie of the Year Award|''Sporting News'' Rookie of the Year Award]], which was voted on by 488 major league players and 30 managers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20071015&content_id=2267061&vkey=ps2007news&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=290147 SportingNews.com \u2013 Your expert source for MLB Baseball stats, scores, standings, blogs and fantasy news from MLB Baseball columnists<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071016084533/http://www.sportingnews.com/yourturn/viewtopic.php?t=290147 |date=October 16, 2007 }}</ref> He lost out to Braun for the 2007 [[Baseball America Rookie of the Year Award|''Baseball America'' Rookie of the Year Award]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Haudricourt |first=Tom |url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/today/majors/features/265033.html |title=\"Record-Setting Bat Propels Braun,\" Baseball America, 10/17/07, accessed 10/18/07 |publisher=Baseballamerica.com |date=October 17, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> in the vote for the [[Players Choice Awards|2007 Players Choice NL Most Outstanding Rookie]] by their fellow major league players,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allamericanpatriots.com/48735746_sports_major_league_baseball_players_recognize_top_rookie_each_league |title=Major League Baseball Players Recognize Top Rookie in Each League |publisher=All American Patriots |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110517030453/http://www.allamericanpatriots.com/48735746_sports_major_league_baseball_players_recognize_top_rookie_each_league |archivedate=May 17, 2011  }}</ref> Fans voted Tulowitzki the ''[[This Year in Baseball Awards|This Year in Baseball]]'' Rookie of the Year, with 27.6% of the vote, ahead of [[Boston Red Sox]] [[second baseman]] [[Dustin Pedroia]] (26.3%) and Braun (22.3%).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/awards/y2007/tyib/index.jsp |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: 2007 This Year in Baseball Awards |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki was selected to the [[Topps All-Star Rookie Rosters|2007 Topps Major League Rookie All-Star Team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071126&content_id=2307272&vkey=pr_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |title=\"Topps announces the 49th annual Topps Major League Rookie All-Star Team,\" KansasCity.Royals.mlb.com, 11/26/07, accessed 11/26/07 |publisher=Kansascity.royals.mlb.com |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511224852/http://kansascity.royals.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071126&content_id=2307272&vkey=pr_kc&fext=.jsp&c_id=kc |archivedate=May 11, 2008  }}</ref>\n\n[[Image:TroyTulowitzki.jpg|thumb|200px| Tulowitzki catching a [[Glossary of baseball (P)#pop|pop-up]] in game four of the [[2007 World Series]]]]\n\nOn October 1, 2007, in the one-game [[2007 National League Wild Card tie-breaker game|Wild Card tie-breaker]] against the San Diego Padres, Tulowitzki went 4-for-7 with three extra-base hits and scored the tying run in the bottom of the 13th inning. The Rockies won the game, 9\u20138, and entered the playoffs as the NL [[wild card (sports)|wild card]] team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=271001127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Padres vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 1, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=October 1, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> They faced the [[Philadelphia Phillies]] in the [[2007 National League Division Series|National League Division Series]]. On October 4, 2007, in the second game of the series, Tulowitzki and [[left fielder]] [[Matt Holliday]] hit back-to-back first-pitch homers in the first inning to begin a 10\u20135 win, and the Rockies headed to Denver with a 2\u20130 lead in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=271004122 |title=ESPN \u2013 Rockies vs. Phillies \u2013 Recap \u2013 October 4, 2007 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=October 4, 2007 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The Rockies went on to complete a three-game sweep of the Phillies, and advanced to the [[2007 National League Championship Series|National League Championship Series]], in which they swept the Arizona Diamondbacks in four games. Colorado then played the [[Boston Red Sox]] in the [[2007 World Series|World Series]], which was the first ever World Series appearance in Rockies history. Boston swept Colorado in four games. Tulowitzki batted .195 in the postseason, with a .267 [[on-base percentage]] and 15 strikeouts in 41 at-bats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/7401470 |title=FOX Sports on MSN \u2013 Nine innings: Here's the dish on Cabrera |publisher=Msn.foxsports.com |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071130090751/http://msn.foxsports.com/mlb/story/7401470 |archivedate=November 30, 2007  }}</ref>\n\nOn January 23, [[2008 Colorado Rockies season|2008]], Tulowitzki signed a six-year, $31-million contract extension with the Rockies.<ref name=contractextension>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080120&content_id=2351593&vkey=hotstove2007&fext=.jsp |title=The Official Site of Major League Baseball: News: Major League Baseball News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The deal, which also included a club option for 2014, was the largest-ever contract for a player with less than two years experience until Ryan Braun signed an eight-year, $45-million contract extension with the Brewers on May 15, 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080515&content_id=2705204&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb&partnered=rss_mlb |title=Brewers sign Braun to eight-year deal |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 29, 2008, in a 3\u20132 road win over the [[San Francisco Giants]], Tulowitzki tore a left [[quadriceps tendon]] during a defensive play in the first inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080501&content_id=2623323&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Tulowitzki out at least until All-Star break |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110927221905/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20080501&content_id=2623323&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=September 27, 2011  }}</ref> He returned to the Rockies, starting at shortstop, on June 20, in a 7\u20132 home loss against the [[New York Mets]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=280620127 |title=ESPN \u2013 Mets vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 June 20, 2008 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=June 20, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> On July 5, 2008, Tulowitzki went back on the disabled list after cutting his right palm in the previous day's 18\u201317 home win over the [[Florida Marlins]]. The injury occurred in the bottom of the seventh inning when Tulowitzki slammed a maple bat into the ground in frustration. The incident took place after he was taken out of the game in that same inning; however, he noted that the frustration leading up to his injury wasn't due to being taken out, saying, \"I was a little bit frustrated, not at the move. If anything, I thought it was the right move. I came in the hallway, grabbed a bat, hit it on the ground and the bat exploded in my hand and cut open my palm running up to my index finger.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3474695 |title=ESPN \u2013 Tulowitzki placed on 15-day DL after cutting hand smashing bat \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 5, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> The cut required 16 stitches, but no damage was done to any tendons or nerves. Tulowitzki returned to the Rockies lineup, starting at shortstop, on July 21, 2008, in a 16\u201310 home loss against the [[Los Angeles Dodgers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=280721127&action=playvideo&hcmp=motion |title=ESPN \u2013 Dodgers vs. Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 July 21, 2008 |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 21, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He recorded a career-high five hits during the game, as he went 5-for-5 with one RBI.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3499586 |title=ESPN \u2013 Tulowitzki has career-high five hits in Rockies' return \u2013 MLB |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=July 22, 2008 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> After returning on July 21 he has had six multi-hit games in his past eight games. In 38 games prior to July 21, Tulowitzki had six multi-hit games.<ref>{{cite web|author=Mid 5th |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/players/profile?playerId=28567 |title=ESPN \u2013 Troy Tulowitzki Stats, News, Photos \u2013 Colorado Rockies |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki ended the 2008 season with a .263 batting average, eight home runs, and 46 RBIs in 101 games.<ref name=br/>\n\n====2009\u20132011====\nOn August 10, 2009, Tulowitzki [[hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]] as part of an 11\u20135 home win over the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=290810127 |title=Chicago Cubs vs. Colorado Rockies \u2013 Recap \u2013 August 10, 2009 \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=August 10, 2009 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He also had a career-high seven RBIs, which tied for the third-most RBIs in MLB history in a game for a player who hit for the cycle. Tulowitzki became the fifth Rockies player to hit for the cycle. He also was the second player in MLB history to hit for the cycle and record an unassisted triple play in a career. Tulowitzki hit a career-high 32 home runs during the season and had a .552 slugging percentage, both of which led all MLB shortstops. He was second in RBIs (92), triples (9), walks (73) and on-base plus slugging percentage (.930).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/touchingbase/2009/08/oh-boy-troy.html |location=New York |work=Daily News |title=Oh Boy, Troy! |first=Jesse |last=Spector |date=August 10, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813091239/http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/touchingbase/2009/08/oh-boy-troy.html |archivedate=August 13, 2009  }}</ref> He finished fifth in voting by the [[Baseball Writers' Association of America]] for [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|National League MVP]].<ref name=2009mvpvoting>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091115&content_id=7669452 |title=Third time is charming for MVP Pujols &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:IMG 1880 Troy Tulowitzki.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Tulowitzki with the Rockies in 2010]]\nOn June 17, 2010, Tulowitzki fractured his wrist after being hit by a pitch from [[Minnesota Twins]] reliever [[Alex Burnett]]. He was placed on the disabled list the following day.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100618&content_id=11317530&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Broken left wrist lands Tulowitzki on DL &#124; ColoradoRockies.com: News |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325042954/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100618&content_id=11317530&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=March 25, 2012  }}</ref>\n\nOn July 4, 2010, Tulowitzki was one of two Rockies, along with starting pitcher [[Ubaldo Jim\u00e9nez]], selected as a [[National League]] All-Star to play in the [[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] at [[Angel Stadium of Anaheim]]. It was Tulowitzki's first All-Star appearance, but due to being on the disabled list since June 18 with a fractured wrist, he was replaced by [[New York Mets]] shortstop [[Jos\u00e9 Reyes (shortstop)|Jos\u00e9 Reyes]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100704&content_id=11909034&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |title=Jimenez, Tulowitzki named first-time All-Stars &#124; ColoradoRockies.com: News |publisher=Colorado.rockies.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120325042959/http://colorado.rockies.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20100704&content_id=11909034&vkey=news_col&fext=.jsp&c_id=col |archivedate=March 25, 2012  }}</ref> In September, Tulowitzki hit 14 home runs from September 3 through the 18th, garnering him back-to-back NL Player of the Week honors for September 6\u201312 and 13\u201319.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.denverpost.com/rockies/2010/09/20/rockies-tulo-named-nl-player-of-the-week-again/4829/|title=Rockies' Troy Tulowitzki named NL player of the week -- again|work=On the Rox|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> He also earned his first National League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|Player of the Month]] award for his efforts during the month of September, in which he led all MLB players with 15 home runs, 40 RBI, 30 runs scored and an .800 slugging percentage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20101004&content_id=15412110&vkey=pr_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=Tulowitzki, Lowe voted National League Player, Pitcher of the Month &#124; MLB.com: Official Info |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Only [[Babe Ruth]] had just as many or more home runs (17) and RBIs (43) during that month in MLB history.<ref name=silverslugger2010>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101111&content_id=16073124&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=CarGo, Tulo team up again, win Silver Sluggers &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki finished the 2010 season leading all MLB shortstops in home runs (27), RBIs (95), batting average (.315), on-base percentage (.381), slugging percentage (.568) and on-base plus slugging percentage (.949).<ref name=br/> He placed fifth in voting for [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|National League MVP]] for the second consecutive season.<ref name=2009mvpvoting /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20101122&content_id=16171678&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Votto wins NL MVP by overwhelming margin &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> Tulowitzki picked up his first [[Silver Slugger Award]] for his offensive prowess.<ref name=silverslugger2010 /> On the defensive side, he had the best fielding percentage (.984) and range factor (5.06) among all shortstops in the National League. He earned his second [[Fielding Bible Award]] and first [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]] at shortstop.<ref>[http://www.billjamesonline.net/fieldingbible/the-winners.asp] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100607130709/http://www.billjamesonline.net/fieldingbible/the-winners.asp |date=June 7, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=5788835 |title=Scott Rolen wins Gold Glove in third different uniform \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Sports.espn.go.com |date=November 11, 2010 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> He was also [[ESPN]]'s 2010 Web Gem champion.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fisher |first=John |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/statsinfo/post/_/id/11783/gold-glove-for-pujols-car-go-but-not-utley |title=Gold Glove for Pujols, CarGo but not Utley \u2013 Stats & Info Blog \u2013 ESPN |publisher=Espn.go.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn November 29, 2010, Tulowitzki agreed to sign a six-year extension on top of the three years, with a fourth option year, remaining on his contract. The six-year extension was worth around $120 million, making it the second-largest contract ever signed by a Rockies player (behind Todd Helton's nine-year $141.5 million contract).<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2010/baseball/mlb/11/29/rockies.tulowitzki/ | work=CNN | title=Rockies hand All-Star Tulowitzki six-year, $120 million extension | date=November 29, 2010}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki was elected by his fellow players as a National League reserve for the [[2011 MLB All-Star Game|2011 All-Star Game]] in [[Phoenix, Arizona]], but after an injury to starter [[Jos\u00e9 Reyes (shortstop)|Jos\u00e9 Reyes]] (who was chosen by fans), Tulowitzki became the NL's starting shortstop. He had one hit during the game, which was a single.{{cn|date=April 2018}} Tulowitzki won his second consecutive (third overall) [[Fielding Bible Award]], as the best fielding shortstop in MLB.<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2011 Awards |url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |publisher=The Fielding Bible |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62sERzLeS?url=http://fieldingbible.com/the-winners.asp |archivedate=November 1, 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> He also received his second consecutive [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]] and [[Silver Slugger Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111102&content_id=25873314&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=MLB's top offensive players earn Silver Slugger Awards &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20111101&content_id=25865014&vkey=news_mlb&c_id=mlb |title=Nine first-time winners highlight Gold Gloves &#124; MLB.com: News |publisher=Mlb.mlb.com |date=May 24, 2013 |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====2012\u20132015====\nOn April 1, 2012, during a spring training game against the [[Cleveland Indians]], Tulowitzki was hit by a pitch on the arm by former teammate [[Ubaldo Jim\u00e9nez]]. Both Tulowitzki and Jim\u00e9nez came close to each other while the benches cleared. Jim\u00e9nez received a five-game suspension and an undisclosed fine.\nAs the season progressed, Tulowitzki required surgery on his left groin, which ended his season. The injury happened on May 30, during a doubleheader with the [[Houston Astros]].{{cn|date=January 2019}} He was limited to 47 games, in which he batted .287 with eight home runs and 27 RBIs.<ref name=br/>\n\nOn June 13, 2013, Tulowitzki suffered a fractured right rib in a 5\u20134 loss to the Nationals. He was placed on the 15-day disabled list and missed 25 games. Despite the injury, Tulowitzki was selected for the 2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game. Teammates [[Carlos Gonz\u00e1lez (baseball)|Carlos Gonz\u00e1lez]] and [[Michael Cuddyer]] were also selected, and all three players were in the starting lineup for the National League. Tulowitzki hit .312 in 126 games in 2013, with 25 home runs and 82 RBIs.<ref name=br/>\n\nTulowitzki started 2014 by batting .364 in April with seven home runs, nine doubles, and 22 RBIs. His hot start earned him the [[NL Player of the Month]] honors for April. On May 3, Tulowitzki singled for his 1,000th career hit in a game against the [[New York Mets]]. He injured his left hip during a July 20 game, and  underwent labral repair surgery on August 15, which ended his season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Silva|first1=Drew|title=Troy Tulowitzki to undergo season-ending hip surgery|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2014/08/13/troy-tulowitzki-to-undergo-season-ending-hip-surgery/|work=NBC Sports|date=August 13, 2014}}</ref> Tulowitzki finished the campaign with a .340 batting average in 91 games played. Despite his injury shortened season, he hit 21 home runs and 58 RBI.<ref name=br/>\n\nTulowitzki made his fifth All-Star team in 2015 as a replacement for the injured [[Dee Gordon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hardballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/07/11/troy-tulowitzki-replaces-dee-gordon-on-the-nl-all-star-team/|title=Troy Tulowitzki replaces Dee Gordon on the NL All-Star team - HardballTalk|work=nbcsports.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref> He batted .300 with 12 home runs and 53 RBIs in 87 games with the Rockies before being traded.<ref name=br/>\n\n===Toronto Blue Jays===\n====Rest of 2015====\n[[File:Tulo_Swinging_2016.jpg|thumb|right|270px|Tulowitzki about to hit a pitch during Spring Training 2016.]]\nOn July 28, 2015, Tulowitzki was traded, along with teammate [[LaTroy Hawkins]], to the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] in exchange for [[Jos\u00e9 Reyes (shortstop)|Jos\u00e9 Reyes]], [[Jeff Hoffman]], [[Miguel Castro]] and [[Jes\u00fas Tinoco]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/139167952/rockies-trade-troy-tulowitzki-to-blue-jays|title=Tulo Toronto-bound; Rockies get Reyes|last=Chisholm|first=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> Upon being informed of the trade during the middle of the ninth inning of a game at the [[Chicago Cubs]], as Blue Jays and Rockies management had kept negotiations secret from the media, Tulowitzki reportedly yelled at Rockies general manager [[Jeff Bridich]] and vowed never to speak to him or other members of the Rockies front office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/columnist/bob-nightengale/2016/02/29/troy-tulowitzki-still-seething-over-rockie-exit-denver/81085588/|title=Troy Tulowitzki still seething over Rockie exit from Denver|last=Nightengale|first=Bob|work=usatoday.com|date=February 29, 2016|accessdate=June 14, 2016}}</ref> Tulowitzki expressed mixed emotions about the trade, but stated, \"I get the chance to play for a contender, and maybe this will revive my career a little bit.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/13334658/troy-tulowitzki-says-was-blindsided-trade-colorado-rockies-toronto-blue-jays|title=Troy Tulowitzki says he was \"shocked\" by trade to Blue Jays|last=Gregorson|first=Derrick|work=ESPN.com|date=July 28, 2015|accessdate=July 28, 2015}}</ref> \n\nTulowitzki made his debut with the Blue Jays on July 29, and went 3-for-5 with a home run, two doubles, three RBIs and three runs scored.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rutsey|first1=Mike|title=Blue Jays' Tulowitzki special in debut, a romp over Phillies|url=http://www.torontosun.com/2015/07/29/blue-jays-tulowitzki-special-in-debut-a-romp-over-phillies|accessdate=July 29, 2015|publisher=Toronto Sun|date=July 29, 2015}}</ref> During a game against the [[New York Yankees]] on September 12, Tulowitzki collided with teammate [[Kevin Pillar]] while backpedaling to catch a fly ball in centerfield, and had to leave the game. He was expected to be out for a minimum of 2-3 weeks due to a cracked shoulder blade.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Chisholm|first1=Gregor|title=Tentative timetable has Tulo out 2-3 weeks|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/149078024/troy-tulowitzki-could-return-by-end-of-season|work=MLB.com|accessdate=September 13, 2015}}</ref> Tulowitzki returned to the lineup shortly before the end of the season after missing 18 games, and in total, appeared in 41 games for the Blue Jays in 2015, batting .239 with five home runs and 17 RBIs.<ref name=br/> The Blue Jays had a record of 50-51 and stood at fourth place in the AL East, but Tulowitzki's arrival helped the Jays go 43-18 for the rest of the regular season to capture the AL East Division title and earn their first playoff berth since 1993.<ref>[https://www.cp24.com/sports/newly-retired-shortstop-tulowitzki-reflects-on-time-with-blue-jays-1.4528408]</ref> \n\nTulowitzki played in all 5 games of the [[2015 American League Division Series]], batting .095 with one home run and four RBIs.<ref name=br/> In the third game of the [[2015 American League Championship Series]], Tulowitzki hit a three-run home run and was later ejected, becoming the first American League player to be ejected from a postseason game since [[Dwight Gooden]] in 1998.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2286829/blue-jays-troy-tulowitzki-ejected-from-game-3-of-alcs/|title=Blue Jays\u2019 Troy Tulowitzki ejected from Game 3 of ALCS|last=Coutu|first=Melissa|work=globalnews.ca|date=October 19, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref> The Blue Jays won the game, 11\u20138.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/154967532/blue-jays-beat-royals-in-game-3-of-alcs|title=Blue Jays outslug KC to trim ALCS deficit|last1=Chisholm|first1=Gregor|last2=Flanagan|first2=Jeffrey|work=MLB.com|date=October 20, 2015|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref> The Jays advanced to the [[2015 American League Championship Series|American League Championship Series]], which was won by the [[Kansas City Royals]] in six games.\n\n====2016&ndash;2018====\nOn May 13, 2016, Tulowitzki hit his 200th career home run in a win over the [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bluejays.mlb.com/news/article/178003026/ra-dickey-leads-blue-jays-over-rangers|title=Blue Jays handle Texas with R.A. dealing|last1=Sullivan|first1=T.R.|last2=Chisholm|first2=Gregor|work=MLB.com|date=May 13, 2016|accessdate=May 14, 2016}}</ref> On May 28, he was placed on the 15-day disabled list due to a right quad strain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-place-tulowitzki-15-day-dl-activate-loup/|title=Blue Jays place Tulowitzki on 15-day DL, activate Loup|last=Zwelling|first=Arden|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=May 28, 2016|accessdate=May 29, 2016}}</ref> He was reactivated on June 18, having missed 20 games due to the injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bluebirdbanter.com/2016/6/18/11969012/troy-tulowitzki-activated-andy-burns-sent-down |title=Troy Tulowitzki activated, Andy Burns sent down |first=Tom |last=Dakers |date=June 18, 2016 |accessdate=June 18, 2016 |work=Bluebird Banter}}</ref> Tulowitzki struggled in 2016, batting a career low .254 in 131 games, though he also hit 24 home runs with 79 RBIs.\n\nTulowitzki was placed on the 10-day disabled list on April 22, 2017 after suffering a hamstring injury.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2655713-troy-tulowitzki-placed-on-10-day-dl-by-blue-jays-with-hamstring-injury|title=Troy Tulowitzki Placed on 10-Day DL by Blue Jays with Hamstring Injury|last=Wells|first=Adam|work=Bleacher Report|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> He returned to the lineup on May 26 after missing 31 games.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/players/gl.fcgi?id=tulowtr01&t=b&year=2017|title=Troy Tulowitzki 2017 Batting Gamelogs|website=[[Baseball-Reference.com]]|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> On July 29, Tulowitzki was placed back on the disabled list with a sprained right ankle, which he injured running to first base.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2707397-troy-tulowitzki-placed-on-10-day-dl-with-ankle-injury|title=Troy Tulowitzki Placed on 10-Day DL with Ankle Injury|last=Wells|first=Adam|work=Bleacher Report|access-date=August 9, 2017}}</ref> He was later diagnosed with ligament damage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/blue-jays-troy-tulowitzki-diagnosed-with-ligament-damage-to-ankle/|title=Blue Jays' Troy Tulowitzki: Diagnosed with ligament damage to ankle|work=CBSSports.com|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref> On August 9, he was moved to the 60-day disabled list, ruling him out for the season. In 66 games, Tulowitzki hit .249 with seven home runs and 26 RBIs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-transfer-troy-tulowitzki-60-day-dl/|title=Blue Jays transfer Troy Tulowitzki to 60-day DL|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=August 9, 2017|accessdate=August 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nEarly in 2018 spring training, it was announced that Tulowitzki had a [[bone spur]] in his right ankle, and that he would miss the start of the [[Grapefruit League]] season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/blue-jays-troy-tulowitzki-dealing-with-bone-spur/|title=Blue Jays' Troy Tulowitzki: Dealing with bone spur|work=cbssports.com|date=February 14, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref> On March 4, [[John Gibbons]] stated Tulowitzki was unlikely to be ready for [[Opening Day]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-tulowitzki-not-expected-ready-opening-day/|title=Blue Jays\u2019 Tulowitzki not expected to be ready for opening day|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=March 4, 2018|accessdate=March 4, 2018}}</ref> Tulowitzki did not appear in any spring training games, and was placed on the 60-day disabled list to begin the year. On March 30, it was announced that his bone spurs required surgery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/injured-blue-jays-shortstop-troy-tulowitzki-surgery-monday/|title=Injured Blue Jays shortstop Troy Tulowitzki to have surgery Monday|last=Loung|first=Steven|work=[[Sportsnet]]|date=March 30, 2018|accessdate=March 30, 2018}}</ref> He missed the entire 2018 season. On December 11, 2018, Tulowitzki was released by the Blue Jays.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/baseball/mlb/blue-jays-release-shortstop-troy-tulowitzki/ |title=Blue Jays release shortstop Troy Tulowitzki |publisher=Sportsnet.ca |date=December 11, 2018 |accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref> The Blue Jays still owe $38&nbsp;million on the two remaining years of Tulowitzki's contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://apnews.com/8e5fc46ce7344aba845b83283575b34e|title=Troy Tulowitzki released by Blue Jays, owed $38 million|date=December 12, 2018|website=AP NEWS|accessdate=January 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===New York Yankees===\nOn January 4, 2019, Tulowitzki signed a one year contract with the [[New York Yankees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25664749/yankees-bolster-infield-agree-veteran-ss-troy-tulowitzki |title=Yankees bolster infield, agree with veteran SS Troy Tulowitzki |publisher=Espn.com |date=2019-01-04 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> They paid him the major league minimum salary of $555,000 and the contract included a no-trade clause.<ref>{{cite web|last=Martin |first=Dan |url=https://nypost.com/2019/01/06/the-concession-that-brought-troy-tulowitzki-to-the-yankees/ |title=The concession that brought Troy Tulowitzki to the Yankees |publisher=Nypost.com |date=2019-01-06 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> He won the starting shortstop job with [[Didi Gregorius]] injured for the start of the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/25685967/troy-tulowitzki-new-york-yankees-opportunity-earn-starting-shortstop-job-gm-brian-cashman-says |title=Troy Tulowitzki of New York Yankees will have opportunity to earn starting shortstop job, GM Brian Cashman says |publisher=Espn.com |date=2019-01-07 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> \n\nHe hit his first home run as a yankee and also his last professional home run, a solo shot at bottom 9-inning, against [Baltimore Orioles]]' and former yankees left-handed reliever [[Richard Bleier]] on March 30, 2019.\n\nAfter playing in five games to begin the season, he went on the IL with a left calf strain.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoch |first=Bryan |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/a-look-at-the-yankees-injury-timetables |title=A look at the Yankees' injury timetables |publisher=MLB.com |date=2019-06-29 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref> On June 7, he was transferred to the 60-day injured list.\n\nOn July 25, Tulowitzki announced his retirement from Major League Baseball through a statement by the Yankees.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hoch |first=Bryan |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/troy-tulowitzki-retires |title=Troy Tulowitzki retires |publisher=MLB.com |date=2018-05-24 |accessdate=2019-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nUpon retiring as a player, Tulowitzki was hired by the [[Texas Longhorns baseball|Texas Longhorns]] as an assistant coach.<ref>https://www.si.com/mlb/2019/07/25/troy-tulowitzki-retires-yankees-rockies-shortstop</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nTulowitzki is of Polish descent,<ref>{{cite web|last=Brown |first=David |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/mlb/blog/big_league_stew/post/Answer-Man-Troy-Tulowitzki-talks-brackets-Dirt?urn=mlb-228829 |title=Answer Man: Troy Tulowitzki talks brackets, Dirtbags and mullets \u2013 Big League Stew \u2013 MLB Blog \u2013 Yahoo! Sports |publisher=Sports.yahoo.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref> and was born in [[Santa Clara, California]].<ref> {{cite web|url=http://m.mlb.com/player/453064/troy-tulowitzki|title=Troy Tulowitzki Stats, Fantasy & News|work=MLB.com|accessdate=October 20, 2015}}</ref> Tulowitzki attended [[Fremont High School (Sunnyvale, California)|Fremont High School]] in Sunnyvale, California. He played Little League baseball with Sunnyvale National. Tulowitzki has a sister, Tiffany, who plays softball, and a brother, Tyler, who played baseball for [[San Francisco State University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sfstategators.com/roster.aspx?rp_id=1199 |title=San Francisco State University Athletics \u2013 2012 Baseball Roster |publisher=Sfstategators.com |date= |accessdate=August 4, 2013}}</ref>\n\nTulowitzki's favorite player growing up was [[Derek Jeter]]. His jersey number with the Rockies and Blue Jays was No. 2, due to his admiration of Jeter.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_5572993 | work=Denver Post | first=Troy E. | last=Renck | title=Shortstop on way to stardom | date=April 2, 2007}}</ref> In a television interview with [[ESPN]], Tulowitzki stated that his favorite team growing up was the [[Oakland Athletics]] and that his favorite musical artist is [[Jay-Z]].{{cn|date=July 2015}}\n\nIn November 2009, Tulowitzki married his high school sweetheart, Danyll Gammon, in [[Portola Valley, California]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/search/ci_14321332 | work=Denver Post | first=Troy E. | last=Renck | title=Rockies' star Tulowitzki armed with better sense of priorities | date=February 3, 2010}}</ref> In January 2014, the Tulowitzkis became parents to a son, Taz.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denverpost.com/ci_25449515/mark-kiszla-face-colorado-rockies-now-father-too|title=Kiszla: Troy Tulowitzki, face of the Rockies, now a father too|work=denverpost.com|accessdate=July 29, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\n* 5\u00d7 [[National League]] All-Star selection ([[2010 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2010]], [[2011 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2011]], [[2013 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2013]], [[2014 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2014]], [[2015 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2015]])\n* 2\u00d7 National League [[Rawlings Gold Glove Award|Gold Glove]]: Shortstop (2010, 2011)\n* 2\u00d7 National League [[Silver Slugger Award]]: Shortstop (2010, 2011)\n* National League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Month|Player of the Month]] (September 2010)\n* 4\u00d7 National League [[Major League Baseball Player of the Week Award|Player of the Week]] (August 6\u201312, 2007, September 14\u201320, 2009, September 6\u201312, 2010, September 13\u201319, 2010)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Fielding Bible Award]]: Shortstop (2007, 2010, 2011)\n* [[This Year in Baseball Awards|This Year in Baseball]] Rookie of the Year (2007)\n* [[Topps All-Star Rookie Rosters|Topps Major League Rookie All-Star Team]]: Shortstop (2007)\n* National League [[MLB Rookie of the Month Award|Rookie of the Month]] (August 2007)\n* Colorado Rockies Minor League Player of the Year (2006)\n* [[All-Star Futures Game]] (2006)<ref name=calledup/>\n* [[Big West Conference]] All-Star: Shortstop (2004, 2005)\n* [[Palo Alto]] Regional MVP: [[2004 NCAA Division I Baseball Tournament]]\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Biography|Baseball}}\n* [[List of largest sports contracts]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players to hit for the cycle]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball career home run leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscategory}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=453064|espn=28567|br=t/tulowtr01|fangraphs=3531|brm=tulowi001tro|retro=T/Ptulot001}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start-collapsible|header={{s-ach}}}}\n{{succession box|before = [[Francisco Liriano]] |title = [[This Year in Baseball 