{"title_page": "Avi Lubin", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2019}}\n{{advert|date=October 2019}}\n\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Avi Lubin\n| image         = Avi Lubin.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1977\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Israeli\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Art curator\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Avi Lubin''' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d1\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05df}}); born 1977, is an Israeli curator of [[contemporary art]]. As of 2018, he is the curator of Hamidrasha Gallery - Hayarkon 19. Co-founder and co-editor of Tohu Magazine.\n\n==Biography==\nLubin has curated many solo and group exhibitions in public and private locations, as well as museums and alternative spaces.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://daniellegorodenzik.telavivian.com/2019/05/08/avi-lubin/ |title=Avi Lubin |website=TELAVIVIAN |access-date=April 22, 2020}} </ref>   Among them, [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]]; The Genia Schreiber University Art Gallery, [[Tel-Aviv University]]; [[Apexart]], New York; [[Kosova National Art Gallery]]; Kunstverein KunstHaus, Potsdam; Chelouche Gallery, Tel Aviv, and [[Sommer Contemporary Art]], Tel Aviv. In 2015, Lubin co-founded Tohu Magazine together with curator Leah Abir, published in three languages: Hebrew, Arabic and English. In 2018, Lubin was appointed curator of Hamidrasha Gallery - HaYarkon 19. During the same year, Lubin was selected along with artist [[Aya Ben Ron]], to represent Israel in the 58th International Art Exhibition at the [[Venice Biennale]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.labiennale.org/en/art/2019/national-participations/israel  |title=Labiennale - National Participants: Israel |website=Labiennale |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLubin received his M.A. from [[Tel-Aviv University]] in 2009. Between 2013-2018 he served as the coordinator of theoretical studies of the Post-Graduate Fine Arts Program at [[HaMidrasha \u2013 Faculty of the Arts]], [[Beit Berl]]. His articles have been published in academic journals, magazines, monographs and catalogues including [[The American Journal of Psychoanalysis]] and [[NY Arts Magazine]]. Lubin has served as guest lecturer in different academic institutions around the world such as [[School of Visual Arts|The School of Visual Arts]] in New-York<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bioart.sva.edu/lecture-by-avi-lubin/ |title=Lecture by Avi Lubin |website=SVA Bio Art Lab |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>, museums including [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|The Metropolitan Museum of Art]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arlisny.org/event-3589040  |title=A Constant Space of Negotiation: Establishing a Tri-lingual Publication in the Middle East: a presentation by Avi Lubin, co-founder and co-editor of Tohu Magazine |website=arlis na new york |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>, and organizations such as Residency Unlimited.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.residencyunlimited.org/programs/the-meet-lunch-avi-lubin/  |title=Meet Over Lunch: Avi Lubin |website=Residency Unlimited |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nHis partner is artist Tomer Sapir.  <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelouchegallery.com/artistExhibition.php?exhibition_id=1313&id=102 |title=Tomer Sapir - Somthing's Happened to Us, Father | website=Chelouche Gallery |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Hamidrasha Gallery - Hayarkon 19===\n*2019 - '''Two solo shows''', [[Jonas Mekas]] - My Two Families | Efrat Hakimi - Zion\n*2019 - '''Kinderland''', three solo exhibitions: Erkan Ozgen, Oree Holban and [[Raffi Lavie]]\n*2019 - '''Shomer''', solo exhibition by Dor Zlekha Levy<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dorlevy.com/shomer/ |title=Dor Levy |website=Dor Levy |access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* 2018 - '''Interrogations''', three solo exhibitions: David Reeb, Ido Gordon and Ignas Krunglevicius \n* 2018 - '''SACRUM''', solo exhibition by [[Tamar Getter]]\n* 2018 - '''Seven Rituals to Change the Mood''', group exhibition: Sharon Glazberg, Hadassa Goldvicht, Hani Khatib, [[Karam Natour]], Karam Sage, Aya Zaiger, Enrique Ramirez, Assi Meshullam and Public Movement\n\n===Independent Curator===\n* 2019 - '''Field Hospital X''' by [[Aya Ben Ron]]. [[Venice Biennale]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fieldhospitalx.org |title=Field Hospital X |website=Field Hospital X |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> \n* 2018 - '''The Magic Kingdom''', group exhibition: Bat Chen Abramovitch, [[Miros\u0142aw Ba\u0142ka]], Guy Goldstein, Hamodi Gannam, [[Mark Dion]], Oree Holban, Eti Jacobi, [[Orit Ishay]], Erez Israeli, [[Paul McCarthy]], [[Michal Na'aman]], [[Roee Rosen]] and Netally Schlosser. Beit Uri and Rami Nehoshtan; Ashdot Ya'akov, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uri-rami-museum.co.il/he/node/193 |title= The Magic Kingdom | website=Uri and Rami Museum |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2018 - '''Mixed Chromosome''', group exhibition: Guy Aon, [[Karam Natour]], Jacqueline Pearl and Tomer Sapir. MOM ART SPACE; Hamburg, Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://das-gaengeviertel.info/programm/veranstaltungsdetails/termin/2018/02/23/event/tx_cal_phpicalendar/mixed-chromosome.html |title= Mixed Chromosome | website=Das Gaengeviertel |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2018 - '''Fog''', group exhibition: Albert Allgaier, Driton Selmani, Fatmir Mustafa-Karllo, Gazmend Ejupi and Luan Bajraktari. [[Kosova National Art Gallery]]; Pristina, Kosovo.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kosovotwopointzero.com/en/driton-selmani-in-our-region-the-role-of-the-artist-is-to-try-to-touch-a-nerve/ |title= Driton Selmani: In our region the role of the artist is to try to touch a nerve | website=Kosovo 2.0 |access-date=December 15, 2018|date= 2018-06-19 }}</ref>\n*2018 - '''Something's Happened to Us, Father''', solo exhibition by Tomer Sapir. Chelouche Gallery; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelouchegallery.com/artistExhibition.php?exhibition_id=1313&id=102 |title= Something's Happened to Us, Father | website=Chelouche Gallery |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> \n*2017 - '''Perhaps it's Dark, Perhaps Undarkened''', solo exhibition by Udi Charka. Givon Gallery; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.givonartgallery.com/past-exhibitions/udi-charka |title= Perhaps it's Dark, Perhaps Undarkened | website=Givon Gallery |access-date=December 15, 2018|date= 2017-04-05 }}</ref> \n*2016 '''Art School''', group exhibition: [[Michal Na'aman]], Dganit Berest, Gabi Klasmer, [[Roee Rosen]], Angela Klein, Miri Segal, Anisa Ashkar, [[Tsibi Geva]], Philip Rantzer, Ben Hagari, Shahar Yahalom, [[Einat Amir]], Raafat Hattab, Noa Gross, Uri Noam, Dor Zlekkha Levy, Hinda Weiss, Lior Shvil and others. The Helena Rubinstein Pavilion for Contemporary Art, Tel Aviv Museum of Art; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tamuseum.org.il/about-the-exhibition/art-school |title= Art School: Hamidrasha Faculty of Arts at Seventy | website=Tel Aviv Museum of Art |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> \n*2016 - '''Circular Movements''', group exhibition: [[Miroslaw Balka]], Jenny Brockmann, Roey Heifetz, [[Thomas Hirschhorn]], Tomer Sapir and [[Ragnar Kjartansson]]. Kunstverein Kunsthaus; Potsdam, Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kvkhpotsdam.de/circular-movements/ |title= Circular Movements | website=Kunstverein KunstHaus Potsdam |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2015 - '''Half Moon Half Sun''', solo exhibition by [[Orit Ishay]]. Art Cube Artists' Studios; Jerusalem, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artiststudiosjlm.org/half-moon-half-sun.html |title= Half Moon Half Sun | website= Art Cube Artists' Studios |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2014 - '''The Hidden Passengers''', group exhibition: [[Mark Dion]], Michael Hoepfel & Jenny Michel, [[Pierre Huyghe]], [[Roxy Paine]], Tomer Sapir and [[Guido van der Werve]]. Apexart; New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apexart.org/exhibitions/lubin.php |title= The Hidden Passengers | website= Apexart |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2013 - '''Vestige''', exhibition by Miri Segal and [[Gideon Gechtman]]. Art Cube Artists' Studios; Jerusalem, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artiststudiosjlm.org/vestige.html |title= Vestige | website= Art Cube Artists' Studios |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>  \n* 2012 - '''Terra Incognita''', solo exhibition by Tomer Sapir. Chelouche Gallery; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelouchegallery.com/show_exhibition.php?id=96 |title= Terra Incognita | website=Chelouche Gallery |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> \n* 2012 - '''ENTROPY''', group exhibition: Guy Goldstein, Roey Heifetz and Hilla Toony Navok. Art Cube Artists' Studios; Jerusalem, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artiststudiosjlm.org/entropy.html |title= ENTROPY | website= Art Cube Artists' Studios |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>  \n* 2011 - '''The End of History''', group exhibition: [[Alona Rodeh]], Dagmar Rauwald, [[Gaston Zvi Ickowicz]], Guy Goldstein, Hans Stuetzer, Jenny Michel, Michael Hoepfel, [[Nir Alon]], Noa Giniger, Roey Heifetz, Thomas Baldischwyler and Tomer Sapir. K\u00fcnstlerhaus Speckstra\u00dfe and Kutscherh\u00e4user; Hamburg, Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314075023/http://www.schir.net/1212/the-end-of-history.html |title= The End of History | website=archive |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n* 2011 '''Groundwork''', group exhibition: [[Gideon Gechtman]], [[Moshe Gershuni]], [[Michal Helfman]], Shahar Yahalom, Shahar Freddy Kislev, [[Ohad Meromi]], and Tomer Sapir. [[Sommer Contemporary Art]]; Tel Aviv, Israel.\n* 2010 '''Grandfather Paradox''', group exhibition: Noa Giniger, Guy Goldstein, [[Gaston Zvi Ickowicz]] and Tomer Sapir. Chelouche Gallery; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelouchegallery.com/show_exhibition.php?id=77 |title= Grandfather Paradox | website=Chelouche Gallery |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Publications ==\n* Avi Lubin (ed.). [https://8c27e1af-8a2d-4bc3-9cc9-0e1deb54dea8.filesusr.com/ugd/56eaf5_aad203d29da54ffa85aec520d6b8bfc5.pdf \"Tomer Sapir, Research for the Full Cryptotexidermical Index  (Artist Book)\".]\n* Avi Lubin. [https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5c3b4c0945776eee4404c254/t/5ca31311ec212d250ec49f50/1554191122505/Silence+isn%27t+Very+Much+-+text+by+Avi+Lubin.pdf  \"White Noise, Black Silence, a catalogue essay for Guy Golddstein exhibition Once, a Beat, Second Heat at the Petach Tikva Museum of Art\"], 2018.\n* Avi Lubin. [https://138732c9-cf06-4278-9450-256803a51dbb.filesusr.com/ugd/d462ea_913432f243e14967888dc4a601f430b1.pdf \"Perhaps it is no coincidence that the horse's tail is also used for making paintbrushes, a catalogue essay for Tamar Getter: H\u0113liotropion at the Mishkan Museum of Art, Ein Harod]\n* Avi Lubin (co-editor). Hamidrasha Journal Issue #19: Art School \n* Avi Lubin. From Political Action to Depoliticizing Politics: Hannah Arendt, Tali Fahima and the Encounter Between Politics and Israeli Criminal Law. Tel Aviv: Tel Aviv University (MA Thesis), 2009.\n* Avi Lubin. [https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s11231-005-7888-3 \"Society\u2019s Symbolic Order and Political Trials: Toward Sacrificing the Self for the \u201cBig Other\u201d]. American Journal of Psychoanalysis 65.4 (2005): 367\u2013379. {{ISSN|0002-9548}} (print)\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://tohumagazine.com/ Tohu Magazine]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lubin, Avi}}\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Israeli curators]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{BLP sources|date=October 2019}}\n{{advert|date=October 2019}}\n\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Avi Lubin\n| image         = Avi Lubin.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1977\n| birth_place   = \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = Israeli\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Art curator\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = \n}}\n\n'''Avi Lubin''' ({{lang-he|\u05d0\u05d1\u05d9 \u05dc\u05d5\u05d1\u05d9\u05df}}); born 1977, is an Israeli curator of [[contemporary art]]. As of 2018, he is the curator of Hamidrasha Gallery - Hayarkon 19. Co-founder and co-editor of Tohu Magazine.\n\n==Biography==\nLubin has curated many solo and group exhibitions in public and private locations, as well as museums and alternative spaces.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://daniellegorodenzik.telavivian.com/2019/05/08/avi-lubin/ |title=Avi Lubin |website=TELAVIVIAN |access-date=April 22, 2020}} </ref>   Among them, [[Tel Aviv Museum of Art]]; The Genia Schreiber University Art Gallery, [[Tel-Aviv University]]; [[Apexart]], New York; [[Kosova National Art Gallery]]; Kunstverein KunstHaus, Potsdam; Chelouche Gallery, Tel Aviv, and [[Sommer Contemporary Art]], Tel Aviv. In 2015, Lubin co-founded Tohu Magazine together with curator Leah Abir, published in three languages: Hebrew, Arabic and English. In 2018, Lubin was appointed curator of Hamidrasha Gallery - HaYarkon 19. During the same year, Lubin was selected along with artist [[Aya Ben Ron]], to represent Israel in the 58th International Art Exhibition at the [[Venice Biennale]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.labiennale.org/en/art/2019/national-participations/israel  |title=Labiennale - National Participants: Israel |website=Labiennale |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLubin received his M.A. from [[Tel-Aviv University]] in 2009. Between 2013-2018 he served as the coordinator of theoretical studies of the Post-Graduate Fine Arts Program at [[HaMidrasha \u2013 Faculty of the Arts]], [[Beit Berl]]. His articles have been published in academic journals, magazines, monographs and catalogues including [[The American Journal of Psychoanalysis]] and [[NY Arts Magazine]]. Lubin has served as guest lecturer in different academic institutions around the world<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.arlisny.org/event-3589040  |title=A Constant Space of Negotiation: Establishing a Tri-lingual Publication in the Middle East: a presentation by Avi Lubin, co-founder and co-editor of Tohu Magazine |website=arlis na new york |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.residencyunlimited.org/programs/the-meet-lunch-avi-lubin/  |title=Meet Over Lunch: Avi Lubin |website=Residency Unlimitied |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>, including [[School of Visual Arts|The School of Visual Arts]] in New-York<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bioart.sva.edu/lecture-by-avi-lubin/ |title=Lecture by Avi Lubin |website=SVA Bio Art Lab |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref>, and [[University of Potsdam|The University of Potsdam]] in Germany.\n\nHis partner is artist Tomer Sapir.  {{Citation needed|date=October 2019}} \n\n==Exhibitions==\n===Hamidrasha Gallery - Hayarkon 19===\n*2019 - '''Two solo shows''', [[Jonas Mekas]] - My Two Families | Efrat Hakimi - Zion\n*2019 - '''Kinderland''', three solo exhibitions: Erkan Ozgen, Oree Holban and [[Raffi Lavie]]\n*2019 - '''Shomer''', solo exhibition by Dor Zlekha Levy<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dorlevy.com/shomer/ |title=Dor Levy |website=Dor Levy |access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* 2018 - '''Interrogations''', three solo exhibitions: David Reeb, Ido Gordon and Ignas Krunglevicius \n* 2018 - '''SACRUM''', solo exhibition by [[Tamar Getter]]\n* 2018 - '''Seven Rituals to Change the Mood''', group exhibition: Sharon Glazberg, Hadassa Goldvicht, Hani Khatib, [[Karam Natour]], Karam Sage, Aya Zaiger, Enrique Ramirez, Assi Meshullam and Public Movement\n\n===Independent Curator===\n* 2019 - '''Field Hospital X''' by [[Aya Ben Ron]]. [[Venice Biennale]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fieldhospitalx.org |title=Field Hospital X |website=Field Hospital X |access-date=April 22, 2020}}</ref> \n* 2018 - '''The Magic Kingdom''', group exhibition: Bat Chen Abramovitch, [[Miros\u0142aw Ba\u0142ka]], Guy Goldstein, Hamodi Gannam, [[Mark Dion]], Oree Holban, Eti Jacobi, [[Orit Ishay]], Erez Israeli, [[Paul McCarthy]], [[Michal Na'aman]], [[Roee Rosen]] and Netally Schlosser. Beit Uri and Rami Nehoshtan; Ashdot Ya'akov, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.uri-rami-museum.co.il/he/node/193 |title= The Magic Kingdom | website=Uri and Rami Museum |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2018 - '''Mixed Chromosome''', group exhibition: Guy Aon, [[Karam Natour]], Jacqueline Pearl and Tomer Sapir. MOM ART SPACE; Hamburg, Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://das-gaengeviertel.info/programm/veranstaltungsdetails/termin/2018/02/23/event/tx_cal_phpicalendar/mixed-chromosome.html |title= Mixed Chromosome | website=Das Gaengeviertel |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2018 - '''Fog''', group exhibition: Albert Allgaier, Driton Selmani, Fatmir Mustafa-Karllo, Gazmend Ejupi and Luan Bajraktari. [[Kosova National Art Gallery]]; Pristina, Kosovo.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://kosovotwopointzero.com/en/driton-selmani-in-our-region-the-role-of-the-artist-is-to-try-to-touch-a-nerve/ |title= Driton Selmani: In our region the role of the artist is to try to touch a nerve | website=Kosovo 2.0 |access-date=December 15, 2018|date= 2018-06-19 }}</ref>\n*2018 - '''Something's Happened to Us, Father''', solo exhibition by Tomer Sapir. Chelouche Gallery; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chelouchegallery.com/artistExhibition.php?exhibition_id=1313&id=102 |title= Something's Happened to Us, Father | website=Chelouche Gallery |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> \n*2017 - '''Perhaps it's Dark, Perhaps Undarkened''', solo exhibition by Udi Charka. Givon Gallery; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.givonartgallery.com/past-exhibitions/udi-charka |title= Perhaps it's Dark, Perhaps Undarkened | website=Givon Gallery |access-date=December 15, 2018|date= 2017-04-05 }}</ref> \n*2016 '''Art School''', group exhibition: [[Michal Na'aman]], Dganit Berest, Gabi Klasmer, [[Roee Rosen]], Angela Klein, Miri Segal, Anisa Ashkar, [[Tsibi Geva]], Philip Rantzer, Ben Hagari, Shahar Yahalom, [[Einat Amir]], Raafat Hattab, Noa Gross, Uri Noam, Dor Zlekkha Levy, Hinda Weiss, Lior Shvil and others. The Helena Rubinstein Pavilion for Contemporary Art, Tel Aviv Museum of Art; Tel Aviv, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tamuseum.org.il/about-the-exhibition/art-school |title= Art School: Hamidrasha Faculty of Arts at Seventy | website=Tel Aviv Museum of Art |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref> \n*2016 - '''Circular Movements''', group exhibition: [[Miroslaw Balka]], Jenny Brockmann, Roey Heifetz, [[Thomas Hirschhorn]], Tomer Sapir and [[Ragnar Kjartansson]]. Kunstverein Kunsthaus; Potsdam, Germany.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kvkhpotsdam.de/circular-movements/ |title= Circular Movements | website=Kunstverein KunstHaus Potsdam |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2015 - '''Half Moon Half Sun''', solo exhibition by [[Orit Ishay]]. Art Cube Artists' Studios; Jerusalem, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artiststudiosjlm.org/half-moon-half-sun.html |title= Half Moon Half Sun | website= Art Cube Artists' Studios |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2014 - '''The Hidden Passengers''', group exhibition: [[Mark Dion]], Michael Hoepfel & Jenny Michel, [[Pierre Huyghe]], [[Roxy Paine]], Tomer Sapir and [[Guido van der Werve]]. Apexart; New York.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://apexart.org/exhibitions/lubin.php |title= The Hidden Passengers | website= Apexart |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>\n*2013 - '''Vestige''', exhibition by Miri Segal and [[Gideon Gechtman]]. Art Cube Artists' Studios; Jerusalem, Israel.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.artiststudiosjlm.org/vestige.html |title= Vestige | website= Art Cube Artists' Studios |access-date=December 15, 2018}}</ref>  \n* 2012 - '''Terra Incognita''', solo exhibition b